1
00:00:38,178 --> 00:00:40,169
<i>...and I'll tell you what,
the storm system's still moving west.</i>
 
2
00:00:39,280 --> 00:00:42,272
What are you looking at, Caroline?

2
00:00:44,317 --> 00:00:45,875
The wind, Mom.

3
00:00:48,988 --> 00:00:51,388
They say the hurricane is coming.

4
00:00:53,059 --> 00:00:56,222
I'm on a boat.

5
00:00:56,329 --> 00:00:58,593
I'm drifting.

6
00:01:00,934 --> 00:01:03,232
Can I do anything for you, Mom?

7
00:01:04,604 --> 00:01:06,469
Make anything easier?

8
00:01:07,440 --> 00:01:08,839
Oh, sugar...

9
00:01:09,375 --> 00:01:11,639
There's nothing left to do.

10
00:01:12,145 --> 00:01:13,737
Is what it is.

11
00:01:15,248 --> 00:01:18,217
Finding it harder to keep my eyes open.

12
00:01:20,186 --> 00:01:23,314
My mouth's full of cotton.

13
00:01:23,856 --> 00:01:25,983
There, there, Miss Daisy.

14
00:01:26,092 --> 00:01:28,822
You gonna scratch yourself to ribbons.

15
00:01:33,733 --> 00:01:36,531
Do you want any more
medication, Mother?

16
00:01:37,437 --> 00:01:40,634
Doctor said you could have
as much as you want.

17
00:01:40,740 --> 00:01:43,004
No need for anybody to suffer.

18
00:01:57,991 --> 00:02:00,892
A friend told me
that she never had the chance

19
00:02:00,994 --> 00:02:03,292
to say goodbye to her mother.

20
00:02:06,432 --> 00:02:08,764
- I wanted to...
- It's okay.

21
00:02:08,868 --> 00:02:12,395
I wanted to tell you
how much I'm gonna miss you so...

22
00:02:12,872 --> 00:02:13,964
Mom.

23
00:02:15,975 --> 00:02:17,738
Oh, Caroline.

24
00:02:23,549 --> 00:02:25,039
Are you afraid?

25
00:02:25,151 --> 00:02:26,846
I'm curious.

26
00:02:28,621 --> 00:02:30,248
What comes next?

27
00:02:35,795 --> 00:02:40,562
They built the train station in 1918.

28
00:02:41,601 --> 00:02:44,331
My father was there the day it opened.

29
00:02:46,005 --> 00:02:48,701
He said they had

30
00:02:50,643 --> 00:02:51,940
a tuba band playing.

31
00:02:56,716 --> 00:03:00,777
They had the finest clockmaker
in all of the South

32
00:03:01,387 --> 00:03:04,185
to build that glorious clock.

33
00:03:06,059 --> 00:03:07,617
<i>His name was...</i>

34
00:03:09,529 --> 00:03:11,326
Mr. Gateau.

35
00:03:15,702 --> 00:03:16,862
Mr. Cake.

36
00:03:19,439 --> 00:03:23,603
<i>He was married to a Creole
of Evangeline Parish</i>

37
00:03:23,710 --> 00:03:25,940
<i>and they had a son.</i>

38
00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:32,977
<i>Mr. Gateau was, from birth,
absolutely blind.</i>

39
00:03:35,254 --> 00:03:39,486
<i>When their son was old enough,
he joined the army.</i>

40
00:03:40,426 --> 00:03:44,795
<i>And they prayed God would
keep him out of harm's way.</i>

41
00:03:47,734 --> 00:03:52,467
<i>For months,
he did nothing but work on that clock.</i>

42
00:03:56,542 --> 00:03:57,975
<i>One day,</i>

43
00:03:59,345 --> 00:04:01,245
<i>a letter came.</i>

44
00:04:06,486 --> 00:04:10,217
<i>And Mr. Gateau, done for the night,</i>

45
00:04:10,923 --> 00:04:13,414
<i>went up, alone, to bed.</i>

46
00:04:16,095 --> 00:04:18,893
<i>And their son came home.</i>

47
00:04:24,070 --> 00:04:26,868
<i>They buried him in the family plot,</i>

48
00:04:26,973 --> 00:04:30,875
<i>where he would be with them
when their time came.</i>

49
00:04:32,879 --> 00:04:35,973
<i>Mr. Cake worked on his clock,</i>

50
00:04:38,851 --> 00:04:42,446
<i>laboring to finish.</i>

51
00:04:44,357 --> 00:04:47,690
<i>It was a morning to remember.</i>

52
00:04:48,995 --> 00:04:52,123
<i>Papa said
there were people everywhere.</i>

53
00:04:53,566 --> 00:04:56,126
<i>Even Teddy Roosevelt came.</i>

54
00:05:13,886 --> 00:05:15,751
It's running backwards!

55
00:05:17,390 --> 00:05:19,119
I made it that way

56
00:05:20,726 --> 00:05:22,591
so that perhaps the boys
that we lost in the war

57
00:05:22,695 --> 00:05:24,060
might stand and come home again.

58
00:05:28,968 --> 00:05:30,401
<i>Home to farm,</i>

59
00:05:31,504 --> 00:05:32,698
<i>work,</i>

60
00:05:34,273 --> 00:05:35,968
<i>have children.</i>

61
00:05:39,278 --> 00:05:41,746
<i>To live long, full lives.</i>

62
00:05:44,917 --> 00:05:47,613
Perhaps my own son
might come home again.

63
00:05:56,295 --> 00:05:58,820
I'm sorry if I've offended anybody.

64
00:06:00,399 --> 00:06:02,663
I hope you enjoy my clock.

65
00:06:03,569 --> 00:06:07,437
<i>Mr. Cake was never seen again.</i>

66
00:06:11,811 --> 00:06:16,214
<i>Some say he died of a broken heart.</i>

67
00:06:17,984 --> 00:06:20,248
<i>Some say he went to sea.</i>

68
00:06:25,391 --> 00:06:26,551
Excuse me.

69
00:06:26,659 --> 00:06:29,219
Do you mind if I make a call?
Somebody's watching my little boy.

70
00:06:29,328 --> 00:06:30,556
Sure.

71
00:06:40,806 --> 00:06:43,036
I hope I haven't disappointed you.

72
00:06:43,142 --> 00:06:46,236
You couldn't disappoint me.

73
00:06:47,713 --> 00:06:52,582
Well, I know I don't have much
to show for myself.

74
00:06:55,154 --> 00:06:57,588
Find my dark suitcase.

75
00:07:01,961 --> 00:07:04,862
There's a diary.

76
00:07:07,033 --> 00:07:08,091
This?

77
00:07:10,836 --> 00:07:13,737
Could you read it to me?

78
00:07:14,240 --> 00:07:16,538
Is this what you want to do?

79
00:07:16,642 --> 00:07:20,544
I tried to read it
a hundred different times.

80
00:07:21,514 --> 00:07:23,505
Mom, it's not exactly...

81
00:07:23,616 --> 00:07:27,017
It's just the sound of your voice, darling.

82
00:07:27,653 --> 00:07:28,847
Okay.

83
00:07:31,991 --> 00:07:34,960
It's dated April 4th, 1985.

84
00:07:36,095 --> 00:07:38,427
And it says New Orleans.

85
00:07:38,531 --> 00:07:41,261
"This is my last will and testament.

86
00:07:41,367 --> 00:07:45,565
"I don't have much to leave,
few possessions, no money, really.

87
00:07:45,972 --> 00:07:51,205
"I will go out of this world the same way
I came in, alone and with nothing.

88
00:07:51,877 --> 00:07:53,713
"All I have is my story,

89
00:07:53,846 --> 00:07:57,247
"and I'm writing it now
while I still remember it.

90
00:07:58,050 --> 00:08:01,213
"My name is Benjamin.
Benjamin Button. "

91
00:08:01,587 --> 00:08:04,681
<i>And I was born under
unusual circumstances.</i>

92
00:08:05,658 --> 00:08:07,888
<i>The First World War had ended,</i>

93
00:08:08,594 --> 00:08:12,462
<i>and I've been told it was
an especially good night to be born.</i>

94
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:16,261
Thank God it's over!

95
00:08:16,369 --> 00:08:18,166
We won the war!

96
00:08:33,085 --> 00:08:34,882
The Great War is over!

97
00:08:47,166 --> 00:08:48,190
What are you doing here?

98
00:08:48,300 --> 00:08:49,597
Thomas,

99
00:08:50,836 --> 00:08:52,269
I'm afraid she's going to die.

100
00:08:52,371 --> 00:08:53,531
What?

101
00:08:54,707 --> 00:08:58,336
That's enough.
All of you, get away from her.

102
00:09:01,547 --> 00:09:04,641
I came as quickly as I could.
The streets are filled with people.

103
00:09:04,750 --> 00:09:06,012
Thomas.

104
00:09:06,519 --> 00:09:09,113
Promise me he has a place.

105
00:09:11,524 --> 00:09:12,650
Yeah.

106
00:09:14,026 --> 00:09:16,017
<i>She gave her life for me.</i>

107
00:09:17,063 --> 00:09:20,032
<i>And for that, I am forever grateful.</i>

108
00:09:29,642 --> 00:09:31,041
Mr. Button.

109
00:09:46,358 --> 00:09:47,586
Thomas!

110
00:09:47,693 --> 00:09:48,921
Thomas.

111
00:09:50,930 --> 00:09:53,091
Thomas? Where are you going?

112
00:10:21,727 --> 00:10:24,059
Hey! What are you doing there?

113
00:10:25,297 --> 00:10:27,322
What do you have there?

114
00:11:24,990 --> 00:11:27,322
- Come on, Queenie.
- Now, Mr. Weathers!

115
00:11:27,426 --> 00:11:30,793
Come on, now, you know I ain't got
nothing but work to do around here.

116
00:11:30,896 --> 00:11:33,160
- Come on. Just take some time.
- Stop all this foolishness.

117
00:11:36,368 --> 00:11:38,131
The air is sweet.

118
00:11:42,575 --> 00:11:45,635
You look very handsome tonight,
Miss Queenie.

119
00:11:46,979 --> 00:11:49,106
Handsome as I've ever seen.

120
00:11:50,549 --> 00:11:52,779
The brown matches your eyes.

121
00:11:52,885 --> 00:11:54,216
Oh, hush!

122
00:11:55,688 --> 00:11:59,818
Let's see here.
You ain't no slouch yourself.

123
00:12:08,400 --> 00:12:10,197
Hambert's back in town.

124
00:12:10,302 --> 00:12:14,068
He came home legless, but he's home.

125
00:12:15,074 --> 00:12:17,702
I know you were sweet on him one time.

126
00:12:18,244 --> 00:12:20,109
Sweeter than I should've been.

127
00:12:20,212 --> 00:12:22,112
Miss Simone messed herself.

128
00:12:22,214 --> 00:12:23,442
Oh, sweet Jesus.

129
00:12:23,549 --> 00:12:26,074
She got to stop doing that
or it's diapers for her.

130
00:12:26,185 --> 00:12:28,210
- I'll be right there, Miss Jameson!
- Now, Queenie, now come on.

131
00:12:28,320 --> 00:12:30,880
Okay, Queenie'll be right there.

132
00:12:30,990 --> 00:12:32,252
It's awful nice out here.

133
00:12:32,358 --> 00:12:35,555
Come on out back for a moment.
Take your mind off things.

134
00:12:35,661 --> 00:12:36,685
You're so bad.

135
00:12:36,795 --> 00:12:39,263
- What in God's name?
- What's this?

136
00:12:49,642 --> 00:12:51,872
Oh, the Lord done something here.

137
00:12:51,977 --> 00:12:55,469
Hope I didn't hurt it none
stepping on it like that.

138
00:12:55,581 --> 00:12:57,105
We best leave that for the police.

139
00:12:57,216 --> 00:12:58,706
Poor baby.

140
00:12:59,551 --> 00:13:00,882
I'll go.

141
00:13:01,553 --> 00:13:05,216
It's for sure nobody wanted to keep it.
Come on, baby.

142
00:13:07,893 --> 00:13:10,327
Queenie? Where are you, Queenie?

143
00:13:10,429 --> 00:13:12,363
Hold your water! You go deal with it.

144
00:13:12,464 --> 00:13:14,557
Okay. No, go, I'll be back.

145
00:13:15,434 --> 00:13:18,699
Queenie, Apple, she went and messed
herself all over again!

146
00:13:18,804 --> 00:13:20,669
Jane Childress, start her a bath!

147
00:13:20,773 --> 00:13:22,832
And mind your own business,
Mrs. Duprey.

148
00:13:22,942 --> 00:13:24,739
You'll be messing yourself
soon enough.

149
00:13:24,843 --> 00:13:26,401
Somebody stole my necklace.

150
00:13:26,512 --> 00:13:29,447
Okay. All right, Mrs. Hollister,
I'll be right with you, okay?

151
00:13:29,548 --> 00:13:31,743
Go on back upstairs, hear?

152
00:13:38,057 --> 00:13:40,582
You are as ugly as an old pot

153
00:13:40,693 --> 00:13:42,354
but you're still a child of God.

154
00:13:42,461 --> 00:13:44,827
Queenie, Apple,
she won't take a bath without you!

155
00:13:44,930 --> 00:13:46,397
Mercy.

156
00:13:46,498 --> 00:13:48,466
I'll be right there!

157
00:13:51,503 --> 00:13:54,438
Okay. You just wait right here
for me now, okay?

158
00:13:57,776 --> 00:14:02,406
My sister gave me those pearls.
I can't find them anywhere.

159
00:14:02,514 --> 00:14:06,348
- Somebody's been stealing my jewelry.
- They're right here, Mrs. Hollister. See?

160
00:14:06,452 --> 00:14:09,751
Right around your pretty white neck.
Now, come on. Hush all that noise.

161
00:14:09,855 --> 00:14:12,449
- Is Dr. Rose still here?
- I don't know.

162
00:14:15,260 --> 00:14:16,557
Your heart is strong.

163
00:14:16,662 --> 00:14:19,631
You just want to avoid
any undue stimulation.

164
00:14:20,232 --> 00:14:23,326
I trust you ladies
will help me out with that?

165
00:14:23,435 --> 00:14:26,563
I have something.
Could you come downstairs?

166
00:14:30,275 --> 00:14:33,972
Never seen anything like it.
Nearly blind from cataracts.

167
00:14:34,079 --> 00:14:38,140
I'm not sure if he can hear.
His bones indicate severe arthritis.

168
00:14:38,984 --> 00:14:43,353
His skin has lost all elasticity,
and his hands and feet are ossified.

169
00:14:43,455 --> 00:14:48,051
He shows all the deterioration,
the infirmities, not of a newborn,

170
00:14:48,160 --> 00:14:50,788
but of a man well in his 80s
on his way to the grave.

171
00:14:50,896 --> 00:14:51,885
He's dying?

172
00:14:51,997 --> 00:14:55,228
His body is failing him
before his life's begun.

173
00:14:57,603 --> 00:14:59,036
Where'd he come from?

174
00:14:59,138 --> 00:15:03,507
My sister's child. From Lafayette.
She had an unfortunate adventure.

175
00:15:03,609 --> 00:15:07,511
The poor child, he got the worst of it.
Come out white.

176
00:15:10,549 --> 00:15:15,145
There are places for unwanted babies
like these, Queenie.

177
00:15:15,788 --> 00:15:18,450
No room for another mouth to feed here.

178
00:15:18,557 --> 00:15:21,082
The Nolan Foundation,
despite their good intentions,

179
00:15:21,193 --> 00:15:23,957
thinks this place is
a large nuisance as it is.

180
00:15:24,063 --> 00:15:25,077
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

181
00:15:25,177 --> 00:15:26,222
- A baby...
- You said he don't have long.

182
00:15:26,331 --> 00:15:30,893
Queenie, some creatures
aren't meant to survive.

183
00:15:34,306 --> 00:15:38,037
No, this baby, he is a miracle.
That's for certain.

184
00:15:38,143 --> 00:15:41,135
Just not the kind of miracle
one hopes to see.

185
00:15:44,183 --> 00:15:46,674
Y'all listen. Y'all listen up here.

186
00:15:47,453 --> 00:15:48,477
We're gonna have us a visitor

187
00:15:48,587 --> 00:15:51,681
that's gonna be staying with us
for a little while.

188
00:15:51,790 --> 00:15:55,487
My sister had a child
and she couldn't see right by it, so...

189
00:15:57,763 --> 00:15:59,492
He's known as...

190
00:16:02,768 --> 00:16:04,065
Benjamin.

191
00:16:04,736 --> 00:16:06,033
Benjamin.

192
00:16:06,939 --> 00:16:09,874
He's not a well child, so we're gonna
have to take good care of him.

193
00:16:09,975 --> 00:16:11,033
I had 10 children.

194
00:16:11,143 --> 00:16:14,476
There's not a baby I can't care for.
Let me see him.

195
00:16:16,682 --> 00:16:20,311
God in Heaven.
He looks just like my ex-husband.

196
00:16:21,153 --> 00:16:23,781
Look, he's prematurely old.

197
00:16:24,289 --> 00:16:27,816
Dr. Rose said he ain't got much more
time on this earth.

198
00:16:28,160 --> 00:16:29,286
Join the club.

199
00:16:34,399 --> 00:16:35,866
He's smiling!

200
00:16:42,641 --> 00:16:45,303
Hambert sends his
remembrances to you.

201
00:16:55,120 --> 00:16:57,452
Are you right out of your mind?

202
00:16:58,757 --> 00:17:02,124
I know you ain't got all the parts
it takes to make one of your own,

203
00:17:02,227 --> 00:17:03,455
but this ain't yours to keep.

204
00:17:03,562 --> 00:17:05,826
It may not even be humankind.

205
00:17:14,973 --> 00:17:17,373
Mr. Weathers, come back here.

206
00:17:19,711 --> 00:17:20,939
Please.

207
00:17:37,296 --> 00:17:39,856
You never know what's coming for you.

208
00:17:49,875 --> 00:17:52,241
<i>It seemed I had found a home.</i>

209
00:17:55,414 --> 00:17:56,472
Is any of this true?

210
00:17:56,582 --> 00:17:59,949
You have such a lovely voice.

211
00:18:00,519 --> 00:18:05,183
Mom, it's an ancient streetcar token.

212
00:18:06,892 --> 00:18:10,020
That clock just kept going,

213
00:18:11,029 --> 00:18:15,227
year after year after year.

214
00:18:19,538 --> 00:18:21,438
<i>But I didn't know I was a child.</i>

215
00:18:21,540 --> 00:18:24,008
Same old crap every day.

216
00:18:24,910 --> 00:18:27,674
<i>I thought I was like everyone else there.</i>

217
00:18:28,680 --> 00:18:30,841
<i>An old man in the twilight of his life.</i>

218
00:18:30,949 --> 00:18:33,281
Could you make him stop that?

219
00:18:34,286 --> 00:18:37,346
Stop banging that fork.
It's used for eating, not for playing with.

220
00:18:37,456 --> 00:18:40,289
And use your napkin, please,
Mr. Benjamin.

221
00:18:42,661 --> 00:18:43,923
Queenie!

222
00:18:56,008 --> 00:18:57,305
Hey, boy.

223
00:19:04,683 --> 00:19:06,981
<i>Always had a healthy curiosity.</i>

224
00:19:08,153 --> 00:19:11,611
<i>What was up the street?
Or around the next corner?</i>

225
00:19:13,492 --> 00:19:14,789
Go get him!

226
00:19:14,893 --> 00:19:18,590
Benjamin! That is dangerous.
Come back over here.

227
00:19:19,331 --> 00:19:21,060
Stay put, child.

228
00:19:23,435 --> 00:19:25,369
<i>I loved her very much.</i>

229
00:19:26,171 --> 00:19:27,798
<i>She was my mother.</i>

230
00:19:27,906 --> 00:19:29,066
Mama.

231
00:19:29,775 --> 00:19:30,901
Mama.

232
00:19:31,710 --> 00:19:35,476
Some days I feel different
than the day before.

233
00:19:36,915 --> 00:19:40,942
Everybody feels different about
themselves, one way or another.

234
00:19:41,920 --> 00:19:44,218
But we're all going the same way.

235
00:19:45,590 --> 00:19:49,253
Just taking different roads to get there,
that's all.

236
00:19:49,361 --> 00:19:51,829
You're on your own road, Benjamin.

237
00:19:54,599 --> 00:19:57,261
Mama? How much longer I got?

238
00:19:57,769 --> 00:20:01,068
Just be thankful
for what you're given, hear?

239
00:20:01,173 --> 00:20:04,233
You're already here longer
than you're supposed to.

240
00:20:07,145 --> 00:20:10,046
<i>Some nights, I'd have to sleep alone.</i>

241
00:20:18,757 --> 00:20:20,418
<i>I didn't mind.</i>

242
00:20:21,326 --> 00:20:24,056
<i>I would listen to the house breathing.</i>

243
00:20:25,263 --> 00:20:27,322
<i>All those people sleeping.</i>

244
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:30,995
<i>I felt safe.</i>

245
00:20:51,857 --> 00:20:54,451
<i>It was a place of great routine.</i>

246
00:20:54,559 --> 00:20:57,460
<i>Every morning at 5:30,
no matter the weather,</i>

247
00:20:57,562 --> 00:21:01,623
<i>General Winslow, U.S. Army, Retired,
would raise the flag.</i>

248
00:21:04,503 --> 00:21:08,462
<i>Mrs. Sybil Wagner,
once an opera singer of some note,</i>

