500
00:38:13,664 --> 00:38:14,961
<i>I never forgot her...</i>

501
00:38:15,065 --> 00:38:16,555
"... blue eyes. "

502
00:38:18,035 --> 00:38:19,593
Mom?

503
00:38:19,703 --> 00:38:24,470
Did you get that this Benjamin loved you
from the first time that he saw you?

504
00:38:25,743 --> 00:38:28,177
Not many people experience that.

505
00:38:29,680 --> 00:38:31,443
Want me to go on?

506
00:38:33,451 --> 00:38:35,442
He crosses something out.

507
00:38:35,553 --> 00:38:38,852
<i>When that baby came,
things were different.</i>

508
00:38:38,956 --> 00:38:42,289
<i>Your mama gone away
And your daddy gonna stay</i>

509
00:38:42,393 --> 00:38:46,193
<i>Didn't leave nobody but the baby</i>

510
00:38:47,665 --> 00:38:50,259
<i>Babies were born, people died.</i>

511
00:38:51,168 --> 00:38:54,001
<i>A lot of folks been through
that old house.</i>

512
00:38:55,973 --> 00:38:59,204
I've come to say goodbye.
I'm going away.

513
00:38:59,310 --> 00:39:00,572
Going?

514
00:39:01,078 --> 00:39:02,602
Where?

515
00:39:02,713 --> 00:39:04,271
I haven't figured that out yet,

516
00:39:04,381 --> 00:39:06,849
but I'll send you a postcard
when I get there.

517
00:39:06,951 --> 00:39:09,715
What about your friend, the tall lady?

518
00:39:09,820 --> 00:39:11,219
We are not friends anymore.

519
00:39:11,322 --> 00:39:14,587
That's what happens
with tall people sometimes.

520
00:39:14,692 --> 00:39:17,456
Well, goodbye.

521
00:39:36,747 --> 00:39:39,511
<i>Spent a lot of time by myself that year.</i>

522
00:39:40,885 --> 00:39:42,113
Hello?

523
00:39:43,888 --> 00:39:45,651
- Hi.
- I'm moving in today.

524
00:39:45,756 --> 00:39:48,589
Welcome. We've been expecting you.

525
00:39:48,692 --> 00:39:51,718
Can you please show her up
to Mrs. Rousseau's old room?

526
00:39:51,829 --> 00:39:55,162
I'm sorry, but we usually
don't allow dogs in the house.

527
00:39:55,266 --> 00:39:58,258
Well, she's old as the hills.
She's almost blind.

528
00:39:58,369 --> 00:40:01,304
She won't be a bother much longer.

529
00:40:01,405 --> 00:40:05,102
Well, all right,
long as she stays from up underfoot.

530
00:40:05,209 --> 00:40:06,403
Right this way, ma'am.

531
00:40:06,510 --> 00:40:09,638
<i>As hard as I try,
I can't remember her name.</i>

532
00:40:09,747 --> 00:40:12,875
<i>Mrs. Lawson, or Mrs. Hartford.</i>

533
00:40:13,918 --> 00:40:15,681
<i>Maybe it was Maple.</i>

534
00:40:15,786 --> 00:40:18,118
<i>It's funny how sometimes
the people we remember the least</i>

535
00:40:18,222 --> 00:40:20,747
<i>make the greatest impression on us.</i>

536
00:40:21,358 --> 00:40:23,690
<i>I do remember she wore diamonds.</i>

537
00:40:23,794 --> 00:40:27,594
<i>And she always dressed in fine
clothing, as if she was going out.</i>

538
00:40:27,698 --> 00:40:31,259
<i>Although she never did
and nobody ever came to visit her.</i>

539
00:40:33,003 --> 00:40:35,335
<i>She taught me to play the piano.</i>

540
00:40:40,711 --> 00:40:43,339
It's not about how well you play.

541
00:40:44,081 --> 00:40:46,914
It's how you feel
about what you're playing.

542
00:40:47,017 --> 00:40:48,348
Try this.

543
00:41:04,702 --> 00:41:07,933
You can't help putting yourself
in the music.

544
00:41:16,013 --> 00:41:18,004
<i>There were many changes.</i>

545
00:41:18,115 --> 00:41:21,175
<i>Some you could see,
some you couldn't.</i>

546
00:41:22,319 --> 00:41:25,152
<i>Hair had started growing
in all sorts of places,</i>

547
00:41:25,689 --> 00:41:27,657
<i>along with other things.</i>

548
00:41:28,959 --> 00:41:31,689
<i>I felt pretty good, considering.</i>

549
00:41:32,763 --> 00:41:35,425
Darling, the pain.

550
00:41:35,532 --> 00:41:38,057
All right, Mom, I'll get the nurse.

551
00:41:40,604 --> 00:41:43,266
<i>Look at this eye.
This is a major hurricane,</i>

552
00:41:43,841 --> 00:41:46,366
<i>a slow hurricane,
with maximum sustained winds of...</i>

553
00:41:46,477 --> 00:41:48,308
Not doing too good?

554
00:41:49,179 --> 00:41:52,444
Nobody seems to know
whether to stay or leave.

555
00:41:52,549 --> 00:41:54,847
I'm gonna ride it out.

556
00:41:54,952 --> 00:41:57,819
There.
That should make things much easier.

557
00:42:01,258 --> 00:42:04,455
Have you had a chance
to say your goodbyes?

558
00:42:04,561 --> 00:42:08,053
My father waited four hours for
my brother to get here from Boger City.

559
00:42:08,165 --> 00:42:10,133
Couldn't go without him.

560
00:42:10,668 --> 00:42:13,330
- She seems like a sweet woman.
- Yeah.

561
00:42:14,004 --> 00:42:15,699
I haven't had as much time with her
as I would've...

562
00:42:15,806 --> 00:42:17,706
- You busy? I could use your help.
- Excuse me.

563
00:42:17,808 --> 00:42:19,036
Sure.

564
00:42:37,227 --> 00:42:39,252
"Queenie would let me go
with Mr. Daws... "

565
00:42:39,363 --> 00:42:43,163
<i>...to Poverty Point to watch the boats
go up and down the river.</i>

566
00:42:43,267 --> 00:42:45,201
<i>These were hard times.</i>

567
00:42:48,238 --> 00:42:51,935
Did I ever tell you I was struck
by lightning seven times?

568
00:42:52,876 --> 00:42:56,277
Once when I was in the field,
just tending to my cows.

569
00:43:02,820 --> 00:43:05,084
My fourth hand didn't show up.

570
00:43:07,324 --> 00:43:10,782
Anybody want to make $2
for a day's work 'round here?

571
00:43:12,730 --> 00:43:14,425
What's the matter?

572
00:43:14,531 --> 00:43:17,261
Nobody wants to do an honest
day's work for an honest day's pay?

573
00:43:17,401 --> 00:43:18,925
He never pays.

574
00:43:20,404 --> 00:43:22,702
- Nobody wants a job?
- I do.

575
00:43:24,341 --> 00:43:27,174
You got your sea legs about you,
old man?

576
00:43:28,278 --> 00:43:29,643
I think.

577
00:43:33,617 --> 00:43:36,051
Well, that's good enough for me.

578
00:43:36,153 --> 00:43:39,611
Get your ass on board.
We'll sure as hell find out.

579
00:43:45,129 --> 00:43:46,756
<i>I was as happy as I could be.</i>

580
00:43:46,864 --> 00:43:48,126
I need a volunteer!

581
00:43:48,232 --> 00:43:49,563
<i>I would do anything.</i>

582
00:43:49,666 --> 00:43:51,099
Yes, Captain!

583
00:43:51,201 --> 00:43:53,499
Scrape off all this bird shit!

584
00:43:54,238 --> 00:43:55,933
Right away, sir.

585
00:43:56,774 --> 00:44:01,234
<i>And I was actually gonna be paid
for something I would've done for free.</i>

586
00:44:02,913 --> 00:44:05,245
<i>His name was Captain Mike Clark.</i>

587
00:44:06,250 --> 00:44:09,151
<i>He'd been on a tugboat
since he was seven.</i>

588
00:44:10,187 --> 00:44:11,916
Get moving, then.

589
00:44:12,856 --> 00:44:14,346
Come here.

590
00:44:16,426 --> 00:44:19,520
Can you still get it up?

591
00:44:20,898 --> 00:44:22,889
I do every morning.

592
00:44:23,567 --> 00:44:26,968
The old pole, huh? The high, hard one?

593
00:44:27,604 --> 00:44:28,901
I guess.

594
00:44:31,508 --> 00:44:34,136
When was the last time
you had a woman?

595
00:44:36,680 --> 00:44:38,580
- Never.
- Never?

596
00:44:39,082 --> 00:44:41,141
Not that I know of, sir.

597
00:44:41,652 --> 00:44:43,415
Wait a minute, now.

598
00:44:44,221 --> 00:44:48,351
You mean to say you've been
on this earth however many years

599
00:44:48,458 --> 00:44:51,723
and you've never had a woman?

600
00:44:56,400 --> 00:44:59,460
Damn, that's the saddest thing
I've ever heard in my life.

601
00:45:00,938 --> 00:45:02,166
Never?

602
00:45:02,940 --> 00:45:04,032
No.

603
00:45:06,677 --> 00:45:10,773
Well, then, by Jesus,
you are coming with me.

604
00:45:21,792 --> 00:45:23,384
What did your father do?

605
00:45:23,493 --> 00:45:25,518
I never met my father.

606
00:45:25,629 --> 00:45:27,563
You lucky bastard.

607
00:45:28,465 --> 00:45:31,093
All fathers want to do is hold you down.

608
00:45:33,737 --> 00:45:37,138
Out on my father's boat,
workin' the two-a-day,

609
00:45:37,474 --> 00:45:39,908
this little, fat bastard.

610
00:45:40,010 --> 00:45:41,705
"Tug Irish," they called him.

611
00:45:41,812 --> 00:45:45,179
Anyway, I finally work up the nerve
and tell him,

612
00:45:46,083 --> 00:45:49,780
"I don't want to spend the rest of my life
on a goddamn tugboat. "

613
00:45:49,887 --> 00:45:51,855
You know what I'm saying?

614
00:45:52,256 --> 00:45:54,918
You don't want to spend
the rest of your life on a tugboat.

615
00:45:55,025 --> 00:45:57,323
Absolutely! Damn right!

616
00:46:00,097 --> 00:46:02,691
So you know
what my father says to me?

617
00:46:03,533 --> 00:46:07,970
He says,
"Who the hell do you think you are?

618
00:46:08,071 --> 00:46:10,801
"What the hell do you think you can do?"

619
00:46:11,108 --> 00:46:12,769
So I tell him.

620
00:46:13,410 --> 00:46:16,607
"Well, if you're asking,

621
00:46:18,882 --> 00:46:20,907
"I want to be an artist. "

622
00:46:21,485 --> 00:46:23,385
He laughs.

623
00:46:23,887 --> 00:46:28,881
"An artist? God meant for you
to work a tugboat, just like me.

624
00:46:28,992 --> 00:46:31,620
"And that's exactly
what you're gonna do. "

625
00:46:31,728 --> 00:46:34,959
Well, I turned myself into an artist.

626
00:46:37,434 --> 00:46:39,163
A tattoo artist!

627
00:46:41,605 --> 00:46:44,403
I put on every one of these myself.

628
00:46:46,944 --> 00:46:50,744
You have to skin me alive
to take my art away from me now.

629
00:46:51,548 --> 00:46:55,040
When I'm dead,
I'm gonna send him my arm.

630
00:46:56,320 --> 00:46:57,719
That one.

631
00:47:00,057 --> 00:47:02,685
Don't let anyone tell you different.

632
00:47:02,793 --> 00:47:05,387
You gotta do what you're meant to do.

633
00:47:05,495 --> 00:47:08,589
And I happen to be a goddamned artist.

634
00:47:09,199 --> 00:47:11,497
But you're a tugboat captain.

635
00:47:12,102 --> 00:47:13,831
Captain Mike?

636
00:47:13,937 --> 00:47:16,667
We're ready for you and your friend.

637
00:47:18,408 --> 00:47:21,434
Let's go, old timer, eh?
Break your cherry.

638
00:47:22,646 --> 00:47:25,342
- Hello, my lovelies!
- Hey, Captain.

639
00:47:25,482 --> 00:47:26,449
- Hi, Captain.
- Hi.

640
00:47:28,618 --> 00:47:29,710
- Hi.
- Hi.

641
00:47:29,820 --> 00:47:32,846
He gives me the willies.
That is not for me.

642
00:47:34,791 --> 00:47:37,055
How are you tonight, grandpa?

643
00:47:37,728 --> 00:47:39,855
<i>It was a night to remember.</i>

644
00:47:45,602 --> 00:47:49,265
What are you, Dick Tracy or something?
I've got to rest.

645
00:47:50,407 --> 00:47:51,635
Again.

646
00:47:52,943 --> 00:47:55,275
- Thank you.
- No, thank you. You have a nice night.

647
00:47:55,379 --> 00:47:57,506
- Will you be here tomorrow?
- Every night but Sunday.

648
00:47:57,614 --> 00:48:01,311
<i>It sure made me understand
the value of earning a living.</i>

649
00:48:01,952 --> 00:48:03,783
Good night, sweetie. Come back now.

650
00:48:03,887 --> 00:48:06,082
<i>Things money can buy you.</i>

651
00:48:23,774 --> 00:48:25,435
It's nasty out.

652
00:48:25,909 --> 00:48:28,810
Can I offer you a ride somewhere?

653
00:48:30,580 --> 00:48:32,844
Well, that's awfully kind of you, sir.

654
00:48:42,192 --> 00:48:44,660
My name is Thomas, Thomas Button.

655
00:48:45,328 --> 00:48:47,421
- I'm Benjamin.
- Benjamin.

656
00:48:48,698 --> 00:48:50,825
It's a pleasure to know you.

657
00:48:52,369 --> 00:48:55,600
Would you like to stop somewhere
and have a drink?

658
00:48:55,705 --> 00:48:57,070
All right.

659
00:48:58,375 --> 00:49:00,639
Evening, Mr. Button.

660
00:49:05,215 --> 00:49:07,149
What'll it be, sir?

661
00:49:07,884 --> 00:49:10,910
- I'll have whatever he's having.
- Sazerac for the both of us.

662
00:49:11,021 --> 00:49:13,387
With whiskey, not brandy.

663
00:49:13,490 --> 00:49:14,980
You don't drink, do you?

664
00:49:15,092 --> 00:49:17,686
- It's a night for firsts.
- How's that?

665
00:49:17,794 --> 00:49:19,853
I've never been to a brothel, either.

666
00:49:19,963 --> 00:49:22,727
Well, it's an experience.

667
00:49:22,866 --> 00:49:25,960
It certainly is.
There's a time for everything.

668
00:49:26,069 --> 00:49:28,469
- True enough.
- Your drinks.

669
00:49:30,140 --> 00:49:35,339
I don't mean to be rude, but your hands.
Is that painful?

670
00:49:35,679 --> 00:49:38,307
Well, I was born
with some form of disease.

671
00:49:38,415 --> 00:49:39,973
What kind of disease?

672
00:49:40,083 --> 00:49:41,812
I was born old.

673
00:49:43,353 --> 00:49:45,048
- I'm sorry.
- No need to be.

674
00:49:45,155 --> 00:49:47,680
There's nothing wrong with old age.

675
00:49:56,566 --> 00:49:59,592
My wife passed away many years ago.

676
00:50:01,004 --> 00:50:02,835
I'm so, so sorry.

677
00:50:04,307 --> 00:50:06,172
She died in childbirth.

678
00:50:09,679 --> 00:50:12,204
- To children.
- To mothers.

679
00:50:17,053 --> 00:50:19,317
What line of work you in, Mr. Button?

680
00:50:19,422 --> 00:50:23,552
Buttons. Button's Buttons.
There isn't a button that we don't make.

681
00:50:25,762 --> 00:50:28,128
Our biggest competition
is B.F. Goodrich

682
00:50:28,231 --> 00:50:29,960
and his infernal zippers.

683
00:50:30,066 --> 00:50:32,864
Would you gentlemen like
anything else?

684
00:50:32,969 --> 00:50:34,994
One for the road, Benjamin?

685
00:50:35,105 --> 00:50:37,938
Only if you let me pay for it, Mr. Button.

686
00:50:39,209 --> 00:50:41,677
So, what line of work do you do?

687
00:50:43,113 --> 00:50:45,547
I'm a tugboat man.

688
00:50:51,755 --> 00:50:53,780
I enjoyed talking to you.

689
00:50:54,257 --> 00:50:56,384
I enjoyed drinking with you.

690
00:50:59,996 --> 00:51:01,395
Benjamin?

691
00:51:01,498 --> 00:51:04,934
Would you mind if, time to time,
I stopped by and said hello?

692
00:51:05,035 --> 00:51:08,436
Anytime. Good night, Mr. Button.

693
00:51:08,972 --> 00:51:10,735
Good night, Benjamin.

694
00:51:11,474 --> 00:51:12,839
Drive on.

695
00:51:18,515 --> 00:51:19,846
Where have you been?

696
00:51:19,950 --> 00:51:24,944
Nothing. I met some people
and listened to some music.

697
00:51:27,724 --> 00:51:29,919
Oh, sweet Jesus, boy!

698
00:51:30,927 --> 00:51:34,021
<i>Growing up's a funny thing.
Sneaks up on you.</i>

699
00:51:34,965 --> 00:51:39,299
<i>One person is there, then suddenly
somebody else has taken her place.</i>

700
00:51:39,903 --> 00:51:41,564
<i>She wasn't all elbows
and knees anymore.</i>

701
00:51:41,671 --> 00:51:43,366
Benjamin! Come on!

702
00:51:43,740 --> 00:51:45,105
Okay.

703
00:51:46,376 --> 00:51:47,934
<i>I loved those weekends
when she'd come</i>

704
00:51:48,044 --> 00:51:50,842
<i>and spend the night
with her grandmother.</i>

705
00:51:58,922 --> 00:52:01,390
Daisy. Daisy.

706
00:52:02,592 --> 00:52:04,719
You want to see something?

707
00:52:05,895 --> 00:52:10,662
You gotta keep it a secret,
so get dressed. I'll meet you out back.

708
00:52:16,206 --> 00:52:17,571
Come on.

709
00:52:19,376 --> 00:52:22,504
- Can you swim?
- I can do anything you can do.

710
00:52:22,612 --> 00:52:25,206
Here, put this on. We gotta hurry.

711
00:52:38,161 --> 00:52:39,685
Is he okay?

712
00:52:39,796 --> 00:52:41,229
Captain?

713
00:52:42,866 --> 00:52:44,356
Captain Mike?

714
00:52:48,104 --> 00:52:50,800
Morning, Captain. Can you take us out?

715
00:52:51,975 --> 00:52:54,273
Do you know what day it is?

716
00:52:54,377 --> 00:52:55,639
Sunday?

717
00:52:55,745 --> 00:52:57,872
Do you know what that means?

718
00:52:59,215 --> 00:53:01,615
Means I was very drunk last night.

719
00:53:02,218 --> 00:53:04,482
Well, you're drunk every night.

720
00:53:06,956 --> 00:53:09,220
- Is that a girl?
- Close friend.

721
00:53:09,959 --> 00:53:11,051
I want to show her the river.

722
00:53:11,161 --> 00:53:14,460
You're not supposed to go joyriding
with civilians.

723
00:53:15,632 --> 00:53:17,759
I could lose my license.

724
00:53:27,577 --> 00:53:29,044
What are you waiting for?

725
00:53:59,242 --> 00:54:02,336
Pulled in for repair a wounded duck.

726
00:54:03,780 --> 00:54:05,907
She's flying now, huh?

727
00:54:06,449 --> 00:54:08,076
Ahoy, sailor!

728
00:54:12,655 --> 00:54:14,987
I wish we could go with them.

729
00:54:20,997 --> 00:54:23,261
Did you say something, Mom?

730
00:54:31,040 --> 00:54:33,008
It's getting really bad.

731
00:54:35,044 --> 00:54:36,807
Can you hear me, Mom?

732
00:54:39,449 --> 00:54:42,111
Time just seeped out of me.

733
00:54:48,892 --> 00:54:50,689
"Things were changing quickly. "

734
00:54:50,794 --> 00:54:54,890
I don't know how it's possible,
but you seem to have more hair.

735
00:54:56,433 --> 00:54:59,402
What if I told you
that I wasn't getting older,

736
00:54:59,502 --> 00:55:02,801
but I was getting younger
than everybody else?

737
00:55:02,906 --> 00:55:06,808
Well, I'd feel sorry for you,

738
00:55:06,910 --> 00:55:09,743
to have to see everybody you love
die before you do.

739
00:55:09,846 --> 00:55:11,746
It's an awful responsibility.

740
00:55:11,848 --> 00:55:15,409
<i>I'd never thought about life or death
that way before.</i>

741
00:55:17,053 --> 00:55:21,114
Benjamin, we're meant
to lose the people we love.

742
00:55:21,591 --> 00:55:24,958
How else would we know
how important they are to us?

743
00:55:28,064 --> 00:55:32,524
<i>And one fall day, a familiar visitor
came knocking on our door.</i>

744
00:55:34,270 --> 00:55:37,068
You want to go with me
to the drugstore?

745
00:55:47,217 --> 00:55:49,583
<i>She taught me how to play the piano.</i>

746
00:55:49,686 --> 00:55:50,948
- Amen.
- Amen.

747
00:55:51,054 --> 00:55:54,217
<i>And she taught me
what it meant to miss somebody.</i>

748
00:55:58,795 --> 00:56:00,228
Let's go.

749
00:56:01,264 --> 00:56:03,198
<i>I had gone to a brothel.</i>

750
00:56:03,299 --> 00:56:05,597
<i>I'd had my first drink.</i>

751
00:56:05,702 --> 00:56:09,160
<i>Said goodbye to one friend
and buried another.</i>

752
00:56:09,706 --> 00:56:14,575
<i>In 1936, when I was coming to the end
of the 17th year of my life,</i>

753
00:56:14,677 --> 00:56:17,510
<i>I packed my bag, said goodbye.</i>

754
00:56:17,614 --> 00:56:19,946
- Bye, Benjamin.
- Goodbye.

755
00:56:20,049 --> 00:56:24,509
<i>I knew, life being what it was,
I'd probably never see them again.</i>

756
00:56:26,723 --> 00:56:28,350
Bye, Mr. Benjamin.

757
00:56:28,458 --> 00:56:30,926
- Good luck to you, son.
- Thank you.

758
00:56:35,465 --> 00:56:38,366
- I love you, Mama.
- I love you, too, baby.

759
00:56:39,569 --> 00:56:42,800
I want you to say your prayers
every night, hear?

760
00:56:47,677 --> 00:56:49,702
Be safe, hear?

761
00:57:01,124 --> 00:57:02,489
Benjamin!

762
00:57:05,595 --> 00:57:08,223
- Where you going?
- To sea.

763
00:57:09,632 --> 00:57:11,691
I'll send you a postcard.

764
00:57:13,536 --> 00:57:15,470
From everywhere.

765
00:57:15,572 --> 00:57:18,166
Write me a postcard from everywhere.

766
00:57:32,689 --> 00:57:34,554
Can you imagine?

767
00:57:36,960 --> 00:57:43,058
He sent me a postcard
from everywhere he went.

768
00:57:44,634 --> 00:57:46,602
Every place he worked.

769
00:57:47,937 --> 00:57:50,997
Newfoundland. Baffin Bay.

770
00:57:51,608 --> 00:57:54,668
Glasgow. Liverpool. Narvik.

771
00:57:55,478 --> 00:58:00,211
He had gone with that Captain Mike.

772
00:58:02,251 --> 00:58:04,481
<i>Captain Mike had contracted
for three years</i>

773
00:58:04,587 --> 00:58:06,885
<i>with Moran Brothers Tug and Salvage.</i>

774
00:58:06,990 --> 00:58:10,858
<i>The old ship had been refitted with
a diesel engine and a new sea winch.</i>

775
00:58:10,960 --> 00:58:13,861
<i>We went around Florida
and up the Atlantic seaboard.</i>

776
00:58:13,963 --> 00:58:17,364
<i>We were a crew of seven now.
Captain Mike and me.</i>

777
00:58:17,467 --> 00:58:20,800
<i>Cookie, Prentiss Mayes
from Wilmington, Delaware.</i>

778
00:58:20,903 --> 00:58:23,303
<i>The Brody twins, Rick and Vic,</i>

779
00:58:23,406 --> 00:58:25,636
<i>who got along fine at sea
but, for some reason,</i>

780
00:58:25,742 --> 00:58:28,802
<i>once they were on dry land
couldn't stand the sight of each other.</i>

781
00:58:28,911 --> 00:58:32,472
You know, one in every
eight boats never returns.

782
00:58:32,582 --> 00:58:34,709
<i>There was John Grimm,
who sure fit his name.</i>

783
00:58:34,817 --> 00:58:36,648
All hands lost at sea.

784
00:58:36,753 --> 00:58:38,983
<i>From Belvedere, South Dakota.</i>

785
00:58:40,390 --> 00:58:43,223
<i>And Pleasant Curtis
from Asheville, Notch.</i>

786
00:58:43,326 --> 00:58:46,489
<i>Never said a word to anyone,
except himself.</i>

787
00:58:48,598 --> 00:58:49,980
I wrote him constantly.

788
00:58:50,080 --> 00:58:51,492
I wrote him constantly.

789
00:58:53,136 --> 00:58:58,130
<i>I told him I had been invited to
audition in New York City</i>

790
00:58:58,708 --> 00:59:01,370
<i>for the School of American Ballet.</i>

791
00:59:01,477 --> 00:59:02,876
Please stay.

792
00:59:02,979 --> 00:59:05,106
Thank you. Thank you.

793
00:59:07,083 --> 00:59:08,345
You can stay.

794
00:59:10,853 --> 00:59:13,913
<i>But I was relegated to the corps.</i>

795
00:59:14,257 --> 00:59:16,623
<i>Another dancing gypsy.</i>

796
00:59:20,930 --> 00:59:22,454
Benjamin!

797
00:59:23,099 --> 00:59:25,567
How is it when you showed up

798
00:59:25,668 --> 00:59:29,536
you were no bigger than a bollard
with one foot in the grave,

799
00:59:29,639 --> 00:59:33,837
but now, either I drink a hell
of a lot more than I think I do,

800
00:59:35,111 --> 00:59:36,738
or you sprouted?

801
00:59:37,647 --> 00:59:39,410
What's your secret?

802
00:59:40,850 --> 00:59:42,408
Well, Captain,

803
00:59:44,220 --> 00:59:46,017
you do drink a lot.

804
00:59:50,827 --> 00:59:55,093
<i>We stayed in a small hotel
with a grand name, The Winter Palace.</i>

805
00:59:55,198 --> 00:59:57,962
You have no idea
what you're talking about.

806
00:59:58,067 --> 01:00:01,525
The hummingbird
is not just another bird.

807
01:00:02,271 --> 01:00:05,968
Its heart rate's 1,200 beats per minute.

808
01:00:07,744 --> 01:00:10,440
Its wings beat 80 times a second.

809
01:00:12,381 --> 01:00:15,373
If you was to stop their wings
from beating,

810
01:00:16,018 --> 01:00:18,851
it would be dead
in less than 10 seconds.

811
01:00:19,856 --> 01:00:22,518
This is no ordinary bird.

812
01:00:23,192 --> 01:00:25,285
This is a frickin' miracle.

813
01:00:28,464 --> 01:00:32,366
They slowed down their wings
with moving pictures,

814
01:00:33,035 --> 01:00:35,230
and you know what they saw?

815
01:00:35,738 --> 01:00:38,536
Their wingtips are doing that.

816
01:00:42,578 --> 01:00:46,412
You know what the figure eight
is the mathematical symbol for?

817
01:00:49,418 --> 01:00:50,942
Infinity.

818
01:00:51,053 --> 01:00:52,384
Infinity!

819
01:00:55,892 --> 01:00:58,793
<i>Everybody, no matter
what differences they had,</i>

820
01:00:58,895 --> 01:01:02,922
<i>the languages, the color of their skin,
had one thing in common.</i>

821
01:01:03,866 --> 01:01:06,232
<i>They were drunk every single night.</i>

822
01:01:06,335 --> 01:01:07,859
Three, please.

823
01:01:07,970 --> 01:01:09,562
Could you hold, dear, for us, please?

824
01:01:09,672 --> 01:01:11,936
Thank you very much. Good evening.

825
01:01:12,041 --> 01:01:14,737
<i>Her name was Elizabeth Abbott.</i>

826
01:01:14,844 --> 01:01:18,143
<i>She was not beautiful.
She was plain as paper.</i>

827
01:01:18,247 --> 01:01:21,045
<i>But she was pretty as any picture to me.</i>

828
01:01:22,351 --> 01:01:24,376
What are you looking at?

829
01:01:26,622 --> 01:01:29,147
If you must know,
we have a longstanding agreement

830
01:01:29,258 --> 01:01:30,623
never to go to bed sober.

831
01:01:30,726 --> 01:01:33,126
- Isn't that right, darling?
- Whatever you say, darling.

832
01:01:33,229 --> 01:01:35,288
<i>Her husband was Walter Abbott.</i>

833
01:01:35,398 --> 01:01:39,300
<i>He was Chief Minister of
the British Trade Mission in Murmansk,</i>

834
01:01:39,402 --> 01:01:41,029
<i>and he was a spy.</i>

835
01:01:41,137 --> 01:01:44,004
- Darling.
- Oh, thank you, my darling.

836
01:01:44,106 --> 01:01:46,131
- Key, darling.
- Oh, yes.

837
01:01:50,646 --> 01:01:53,672
I broke my heel off one of my shoes.

838
01:01:53,783 --> 01:01:57,378
I'm not in the habit of walking about
in my stocking feet.

839
01:02:01,791 --> 01:02:03,952
<i>They were long days there.</i>

840
01:02:11,467 --> 01:02:13,435
<i>And even longer nights.</i>

841
01:02:15,638 --> 01:02:19,199
<i>One particular night,
I was having trouble sleeping.</i>

842
01:02:20,643 --> 01:02:22,167
I'm sorry.

843
01:02:24,046 --> 01:02:25,775
I couldn't sleep.

844
01:02:38,694 --> 01:02:42,152
I was gonna make some tea.
Would you like some?

845
01:02:43,065 --> 01:02:44,896
Oh, no. Thank you.

846
01:03:22,738 --> 01:03:24,296
Milk? Honey?

847
01:03:24,941 --> 01:03:26,875
A bit of honey, please.

848
01:03:27,410 --> 01:03:29,173
I hope you like flies in your honey.

849
01:03:29,278 --> 01:03:30,939
Oh, perhaps not.

850
01:03:45,795 --> 01:03:50,027
Oh, maybe better to let it steep a little.

851
01:03:51,033 --> 01:03:52,227
Steep?

852
01:03:52,601 --> 01:03:53,659
Soak.

853
01:03:53,936 --> 01:03:57,599
I don't know, I mean,
there's a proper way of making tea.

854
01:03:57,707 --> 01:04:00,938
Well, where I'm from,
people just want it to be hot.

855
01:04:01,043 --> 01:04:03,136
Well, quite right.

856
01:04:12,054 --> 01:04:14,454
- Now, you're a seaman.
- A sailor.

857
01:04:14,557 --> 01:04:17,287
I hope you won't think me impolite,
but I have to ask,

858
01:04:17,393 --> 01:04:19,520
aren't you a little old
to be working on a boat?

859
01:04:19,628 --> 01:04:23,029
There's no age limit,
as long as you can do the work.

860
01:04:33,843 --> 01:04:36,141
And you have trouble sleeping?
Thank you.

861
01:04:36,245 --> 01:04:39,442
I didn't think I did.
I usually sleep like a baby.

862
01:04:40,416 --> 01:04:42,850
Something's been keeping me up.

863
01:04:44,086 --> 01:04:45,280
My father, in his 80s,

864
01:04:45,388 --> 01:04:48,653
he was so convinced
he was gonna die in his sleep,

865
01:04:49,291 --> 01:04:52,419
he limited himself
to having afternoon naps.

866
01:04:53,195 --> 01:04:55,959
He was so determined
he was gonna cheat death.

867
01:04:57,133 --> 01:04:58,998
- Did he?
- Did he what?

868
01:04:59,135 --> 01:05:00,762
Die in his sleep?

869
01:05:02,471 --> 01:05:05,065
He died sitting in his favorite chair

870
01:05:05,174 --> 01:05:07,802
listening to his favorite program
on the wireless.

871
01:05:07,910 --> 01:05:10,378
He must have known something.

872
01:05:16,118 --> 01:05:21,181
My husband's the British Trade Minister,
and we've been here for 14 months.

873
01:05:21,290 --> 01:05:24,623
- Good God.
- We were supposed to go to Peking

874
01:05:24,727 --> 01:05:28,185
but it never seemed to work out.

875
01:05:29,665 --> 01:05:31,360
Have you been in the Far East?

876
01:05:31,467 --> 01:05:33,662
No. I've never been anywhere, really.

877
01:05:33,769 --> 01:05:36,203
I mean, outside of harbors.

878
01:05:36,305 --> 01:05:37,966
And where is it that you're from?

879
01:05:38,074 --> 01:05:40,565
New Orleans. Louisiana.

880
01:05:42,078 --> 01:05:44,376
I didn't know there was another.

881
01:05:46,682 --> 01:05:51,710
<i>And she told me about all the places
she had been, and what she had seen.</i>

882
01:05:53,322 --> 01:05:56,223
<i>And we talked till just before the dawn.</i>

883
01:05:57,259 --> 01:05:58,726
I'm just a lush, myself.

884
01:05:58,828 --> 01:06:03,765
<i>And we went back to our rooms,
to our separate lives.</i>

885
01:06:09,205 --> 01:06:12,504
<i>But every night,
we'd meet again in that lobby.</i>

886
01:06:17,847 --> 01:06:21,749
<i>A hotel in the middle of the night
can be a magical place.</i>

887
01:06:24,620 --> 01:06:27,521
<i>A mouse running, and stopping.</i>

888
01:06:28,958 --> 01:06:31,051
<i>A radiator hissing.</i>

889
01:06:32,061 --> 01:06:33,926
<i>A curtain blowing.</i>

890
01:06:37,700 --> 01:06:41,067
<i>There's something peaceful,
even comforting</i>

891
01:06:41,170 --> 01:06:44,401
<i>knowing that the people you love
are asleep in their beds</i>

892
01:06:44,507 --> 01:06:46,737
<i>where nothing can harm them.</i>

893
01:06:49,845 --> 01:06:52,780
<i>Elizabeth and I would lose track
of the night</i>

894
01:06:53,315 --> 01:06:55,476
<i>until just before daybreak.</i>

895
01:06:58,087 --> 01:07:00,885
I think I may have given you
the wrong impression.

896
01:07:00,990 --> 01:07:02,514
Beg pardon?

897
01:07:02,625 --> 01:07:06,425
Well, married women don't customarily
sit around

898
01:07:06,529 --> 01:07:08,554
in the middle of the night
with strange men in hotels.

899
01:07:08,664 --> 01:07:12,191
I wouldn't know what a married woman
does or doesn't do.

900
01:07:17,973 --> 01:07:19,406
Good night.

901
01:07:21,744 --> 01:07:23,041
Murmansk.

902
01:07:25,681 --> 01:07:28,741
"I've met somebody,
and I've fallen in love. "

903
01:07:28,851 --> 01:07:30,045
Mom?

904
01:07:33,889 --> 01:07:36,414
That was over 60 years ago.

905
01:07:37,726 --> 01:07:38,750
Did you love him, Mother?

906
01:07:38,861 --> 01:07:41,625
What does a girl know about love?

907
01:08:15,231 --> 01:08:16,425
Well...

908
01:08:18,934 --> 01:08:22,700
- I'm not dressed.
- Oh, you look splendid, just as you are.

909
01:08:24,974 --> 01:08:28,034
Don't waste any time bothering about
the wine or the cheese in Murmansk,

910
01:08:28,143 --> 01:08:31,169
'cause they're really
completely ordinary,

911
01:08:31,280 --> 01:08:36,240
but the caviar and the vodka

912
01:08:36,819 --> 01:08:40,915
are sublime and plentiful.

913
01:08:44,727 --> 01:08:45,989
So.

914
01:08:51,300 --> 01:08:52,597
Savor it.

915
01:08:54,737 --> 01:08:56,705
And don't eat it all at once,

916
01:08:56,805 --> 01:08:59,899
because that way,
there's nothing left to enjoy.

917
01:09:01,577 --> 01:09:05,911
And now, take a little swallow of vodka
while it's still in your mouth.

918
01:09:20,796 --> 01:09:23,629
You haven't been with many women,
have you?

919
01:09:24,833 --> 01:09:26,460
Not on Sundays.

920
01:09:28,671 --> 01:09:30,400
And you've never had caviar before,
have you?

921
01:09:30,506 --> 01:09:32,133
No, ma'am.

922
01:09:37,980 --> 01:09:39,641
When I was 19,

923
01:09:40,649 --> 01:09:46,918
I attempted to become the first woman
ever to swim the English Channel.

924
01:09:47,923 --> 01:09:49,322
Really?

925
01:09:49,958 --> 01:09:52,984
But the current that day
was so strong that,

926
01:09:53,095 --> 01:09:56,189
for every stroke I took,
I was pushed back two.

927
01:09:56,799 --> 01:09:59,393
<i>I was in the water for 32 hours.</i>

928
01:10:00,369 --> 01:10:04,203
And when I was two miles from Calais,

929
01:10:05,341 --> 01:10:07,070
<i>it started to rain.</i>

930
01:10:07,810 --> 01:10:09,710
That's it! Steady on!

931
01:10:10,245 --> 01:10:12,873
<i>When I couldn't go any further,</i>

932
01:10:14,483 --> 01:10:15,916
I stopped.

933
01:10:17,319 --> 01:10:18,911
<i>I just stopped.</i>

934
01:10:19,521 --> 01:10:24,390
And everybody asked me,
would I try again?

935
01:10:25,127 --> 01:10:26,992
<i>For why wouldn't I?</i>

936
01:10:29,898 --> 01:10:31,593
But I never did.

937
01:10:33,035 --> 01:10:37,267
As a matter of fact, I've never done
anything with my life after that.

938
01:10:41,410 --> 01:10:43,435
Your hands are so coarse.

939
01:10:53,789 --> 01:10:56,349
I can feel the wind in your cheek.

940
01:11:03,132 --> 01:11:05,623
I'm afraid it's the witching hour.

941
01:11:11,540 --> 01:11:14,771
<i>It was the first time
a woman had ever kissed me.</i>

942
01:11:15,344 --> 01:11:17,744
<i>It's something you never forget.</i>

943
01:11:28,257 --> 01:11:30,282
I think you make me feel younger.

944
01:11:30,392 --> 01:11:32,917
You make me feel years younger, too.

945
01:11:33,028 --> 01:11:34,620
I wish I was.

946
01:11:35,631 --> 01:11:37,758
So many things I'd change.

947
01:11:38,467 --> 01:11:40,799
I'd undo all my mistakes.

948
01:11:40,903 --> 01:11:42,598
What mistakes?

949
01:11:45,941 --> 01:11:48,102
I kept waiting, you know?

950
01:11:48,744 --> 01:11:53,238
Thinking that I'd do something
to change my circumstances.

951
01:11:54,516 --> 01:11:56,245
Do something.

952
01:11:57,820 --> 01:12:01,051
Such an awful waste.
You never get it back.

953
01:12:01,523 --> 01:12:02,990
Wasted time.

954
01:12:09,298 --> 01:12:11,698
If we're going to have an affair,

955
01:12:12,434 --> 01:12:15,267
you're never to look at me
during the day.

956
01:12:15,904 --> 01:12:18,839
And we're always to part before sunrise.

957
01:12:19,508 --> 01:12:22,136
And we will never say "I love you. "

958
01:12:23,779 --> 01:12:25,576
Those are the rules.

959
01:12:28,183 --> 01:12:30,344
- Are you cold?
- I'm freezing.

960
01:12:30,452 --> 01:12:32,386
Oh, you! You're frozen.

961
01:12:32,488 --> 01:12:35,685
What an idiot, I'm standing here
in this fur. How thoughtless of me.

962
01:13:09,358 --> 01:13:12,156
<i>She was the first woman
that ever loved me.</i>

963
01:13:15,130 --> 01:13:16,358
You want me to skip some?

964
01:13:16,465 --> 01:13:22,233
No, I'm glad he had somebody
to keep him warm.

965
01:13:25,908 --> 01:13:28,376
"I couldn't wait to see her again. "

966
01:13:41,290 --> 01:13:43,588
<i>We saw each other every night.</i>

967
01:13:44,192 --> 01:13:46,490
<i>We always used the same room.</i>

968
01:13:48,463 --> 01:13:51,796
<i>But each time seemed new
and different.</i>

969
01:13:53,201 --> 01:13:54,634
Come here.

970
01:14:02,110 --> 01:14:03,509
Elizabeth.

971
01:14:04,880 --> 01:14:06,279
Good night.

972
01:14:08,984 --> 01:14:10,611
<i>Until one night.</i>

973
01:14:47,889 --> 01:14:53,486
<i>Yesterday, December 7th, 1941,</i>

974
01:14:53,595 --> 01:14:56,689
<i>a date which will live in infamy...</i>

975
01:14:56,798 --> 01:15:00,928
It's a meeting, a policy meeting
regarding your future,

976
01:15:01,870 --> 01:15:03,428
possibly beyond.

977
01:15:04,840 --> 01:15:07,400
There's been a change of plan, lads.

978
01:15:07,609 --> 01:15:10,203
As you may or may not know,

979
01:15:10,312 --> 01:15:12,906
the Japs bombed
Pearl Harbor yesterday.

980
01:15:13,348 --> 01:15:16,806
Frank D. Roosevelt's asked
each of us to do our part.

981
01:15:17,319 --> 01:15:21,415
<i>The Chelsea's been commissioned
to serve in the United States Navy.</i>

982
01:15:21,857 --> 01:15:25,122
To repair, to salvage, and to rescue.

983
01:15:26,662 --> 01:15:30,996
Anybody doesn't want to go to war,
now is the time to say so.

984
01:15:31,099 --> 01:15:35,297
Once you set foot on that boat,
you're in the Navy, friend.

985
01:15:38,540 --> 01:15:41,566
Yeah, I've been meaning
to talk with you, Mike.

986
01:15:41,677 --> 01:15:43,668
My wife's doing poorly.

987
01:15:43,779 --> 01:15:46,509
I'd like to maybe see her one more time.

988
01:15:48,250 --> 01:15:52,050
You're free to make your way home
any way you can, Mr. Mayes.

989
01:15:57,693 --> 01:15:59,456
Well, if he's leaving, who's gonna cook?

990
01:15:59,561 --> 01:16:03,622
Food poisoning's one of the leading
causes of death at sea.

991
01:16:03,732 --> 01:16:06,098
Right after
inadequate safety equipment.

992
01:16:06,201 --> 01:16:08,829
I can cook, Captain.
Been doing it all my life.

993
01:16:08,937 --> 01:16:13,340
I don't know.
You're a little moody for war, Benjamin.

994
01:16:13,442 --> 01:16:15,410
What the hell?

995
01:16:15,510 --> 01:16:19,844
I'll take any man wants to kick the shite
out of the Japs and the Huns.

996
01:16:21,249 --> 01:16:25,015
That's it, pack your gear.
We're going to war, gentlemen!

997
01:16:31,893 --> 01:16:33,656
<i>She had left a note.</i>

998
01:16:35,030 --> 01:16:37,760
<i>She wrote,
"It was nice to have met you. "</i>

999
01:16:38,533 --> 01:16:40,125
<i>And that was it.</i>

1000
01:16:43,371 --> 01:16:46,431
<i>It wasn't the war any of us expected.</i>

1001
01:16:46,541 --> 01:16:50,170
<i>We would just tow crippled ships,
scraps of metal, really.</i>

1002
01:16:50,779 --> 01:16:53,748
<i>If there was a war, we didn't see it.</i>

1003
01:16:55,650 --> 01:16:59,711
<i>There was a man assigned to us.
The Chief Gunner loved the Navy.</i>

1004
01:16:59,821 --> 01:17:02,016
<i>But most of all, he loved America.</i>

1005
01:17:02,124 --> 01:17:05,025
There is no other country in the world.

1006
01:17:05,127 --> 01:17:06,219
When you spell America...

1007
01:17:06,328 --> 01:17:10,492
<i>His name was Dennis Smith,
and he was a full-blooded Cherokee.</i>

1008
01:17:10,599 --> 01:17:13,693
<i>His family had been Americans
for over 500 years.</i>

1009
01:17:13,802 --> 01:17:18,330
These pacifists.
They say they won't fight on conscience.

1010
01:17:18,440 --> 01:17:22,035
Now, where would be
if everybody decided to act

1011
01:17:22,144 --> 01:17:26,103
- according to their conscience?
- Keep it down, would you, Chief?

1012
01:17:42,330 --> 01:17:45,700
Hey. I've been watching you.

1013
01:17:46,868 --> 01:17:48,665
You seem trustworthy.

1014
01:17:50,472 --> 01:17:52,565
If something happens to me,

1015
01:17:56,645 --> 01:17:59,205
could you see that this gets to my wife?

1016
01:17:59,314 --> 01:18:03,842
<i>He'd given me all of his pay.
Hadn't spent a dime of it.</i>

1017
01:18:05,754 --> 01:18:09,019
I want my family to know
I was thinking about them.

1018
01:18:13,795 --> 01:18:15,626
All hands on deck!

1019
01:18:42,224 --> 01:18:44,419
<i>The war had finally found us.</i>

1020
01:18:47,128 --> 01:18:48,595
All stop!

1021
01:18:51,333 --> 01:18:53,324
Pleasant, man that light.

1022
01:19:01,209 --> 01:19:05,373
<i>A transport carrying 1,300 men
had been split by a torpedo.</i>

1023
01:19:07,782 --> 01:19:10,046
<i>We were first to arrive at the scene.</i>

1024
01:19:10,151 --> 01:19:13,712
- Cut the engines!
- All stop!

1025
01:19:18,860 --> 01:19:20,760
<i>We were the only sound.</i>

1026
01:19:34,709 --> 01:19:36,108
Fellas!

1027
01:19:46,087 --> 01:19:47,145
Sub!

1028
01:19:51,960 --> 01:19:54,758
We sure as hell
can't outrun them fuckers.

1029
01:19:56,498 --> 01:19:58,796
Battle stations!

1030
01:20:08,677 --> 01:20:09,666
Thank you, Chief.

1031
01:20:11,980 --> 01:20:13,072
What?

1032
01:20:26,061 --> 01:20:27,858
Is that the last one?

1033
01:21:49,477 --> 01:21:50,705
Captain!

1034
01:22:06,361 --> 01:22:08,989
They shot the hell out of my painting!

1035
01:22:10,265 --> 01:22:12,096
Give me your other hand.

1036
01:22:17,472 --> 01:22:18,496
You'll be all right, Captain.

1037
01:22:18,606 --> 01:22:22,872
They got a nice spot in Heaven
waiting for you. Nice spot.

1038
01:22:24,412 --> 01:22:27,438
You can be as mad as a mad dog
at the way things went.

1039
01:22:30,452 --> 01:22:34,115
You could swear, curse the Fates.

1040
01:22:36,424 --> 01:22:38,551
But when it comes to the end,

1041
01:22:40,762 --> 01:22:42,491
you have to let go.

1042
01:22:49,504 --> 01:22:50,732
Captain?

1043
01:23:11,593 --> 01:23:14,892
<i>Thirteen hundred and twenty eight men
died that day.</i>

1044
01:23:17,198 --> 01:23:20,429
<i>I said my goodbyes to the Cherokee,
Dennis Smith.</i>

1045
01:23:21,402 --> 01:23:24,599
<i>John Grimm, who was right,
he was gonna die there.</i>

1046
01:23:26,107 --> 01:23:28,803
<i>I sent Pleasant Curtis' wife his money.</i>

1047
01:23:29,644 --> 01:23:32,704
<i>I said goodbye to the twin, Vic Brody,</i>

1048
01:23:32,814 --> 01:23:37,478
<i>and to Mike Clark,
captain of the tugboat Chelsea.</i>

1049
01:23:39,954 --> 01:23:44,414
<i>I said goodbye to all the other men
who had dreams of their own,</i>

1050
01:23:44,526 --> 01:23:47,086
<i>all the men
who wanted to be insurance salesmen</i>

1051
01:23:47,195 --> 01:23:50,130
<i>or doctors or lawyers or Indian chiefs.</i>

1052
01:23:51,199 --> 01:23:52,996
This don't get fixed.

1053
01:23:55,103 --> 01:23:58,163
<i>Out here, death didn't seem natural.</i>

1054
01:24:15,190 --> 01:24:18,353
<i>I'd never seen a hummingbird
that far out to sea.</i>

1055
01:24:19,894 --> 01:24:21,486
<i>Before or since.</i>

1056
01:24:27,517 --> 01:24:33,752
<i>And in May of 1945,
when I was 26 years old,</i>

1057
01:24:33,857 --> 01:24:34,958
<i>I came home.</i>

1058
01:24:35,859 --> 01:24:38,453
I'm ready! I'm ready!

1059
01:24:38,561 --> 01:24:39,926
I'm coming!

1060
01:24:40,830 --> 01:24:44,459
- I'm ready!
- All right, I'm coming, Miss Alfalina.

1061
01:24:44,567 --> 01:24:46,057
- Queenie?
- Yes?

1062
01:24:51,941 --> 01:24:57,846
Sweet Jesus! Oh, you're home!
Oh, Lord, you came back!

1063
01:24:58,748 --> 01:25:00,682
- Let me look at you.
- Who's that, Mama?

1064
01:25:00,784 --> 01:25:04,049
- Child, it's your brother, Benjamin.
- I didn't know he was my brother.

1065
01:25:04,154 --> 01:25:05,815
There's a shitload of things
you don't know, child.

1066
01:25:05,922 --> 01:25:07,082
Get on out there and finish sweeping.

1067
01:25:07,190 --> 01:25:09,351
Come here, wash your hands,
help me with the table. Go on, now.

1068
01:25:09,459 --> 01:25:13,361
Turn around.
You look like you've been born again.

1069
01:25:13,463 --> 01:25:15,727
Younger than the springtime.

1070
01:25:15,832 --> 01:25:19,461
I think that preacher laid hands on you
gave you a second life.

1071
01:25:19,569 --> 01:25:23,198
I knew it that moment I saw you,
you were special.

1072
01:25:23,306 --> 01:25:25,171
I tell you what, my knees are sore,

1073
01:25:25,275 --> 01:25:27,800
'cause I've been on them every night
asking the Lord,

1074
01:25:27,911 --> 01:25:31,642
I said,
"God, just bring him home safely. "

1075
01:25:31,748 --> 01:25:34,239
Remember what I told you?

1076
01:25:34,350 --> 01:25:35,977
"You never know
what's coming for you"?

1077
01:25:36,086 --> 01:25:37,986
That's right. Sit down.

1078
01:25:39,389 --> 01:25:43,485
Well, you learn anything
worth repeating?

1079
01:25:45,595 --> 01:25:49,827
- I sure saw some things.
- Oh, you seen some pain.

1080
01:25:51,334 --> 01:25:54,098
- Some joy, too?
- Sure. Sure, I did.

1081
01:25:54,204 --> 01:25:58,334
Yeah, that's what I want to hear.
Look at you.

1082
01:25:58,441 --> 01:26:01,933
- Where's Tizzy?
- Oh, baby.

1083
01:26:04,414 --> 01:26:08,282
Mr. Weathers died in his sleep
one night last April.

1084
01:26:08,384 --> 01:26:11,842
- Mama, I'm so sorry.
- Don't you worry about that, baby.

1085
01:26:13,590 --> 01:26:16,218
Yeah, well, it's only
one or two of them left now.

1086
01:26:16,326 --> 01:26:17,793
They all just about new.

1087
01:26:17,894 --> 01:26:21,796
Guess they're waiting their turn
like everybody else, huh?

1088
01:26:21,898 --> 01:26:24,628
I'm so glad you're back home with me!

1089
01:26:24,734 --> 01:26:27,862
Now, we're gonna have to find you
a wife and a new job! That's right.

1090
01:26:27,971 --> 01:26:29,836
Come on in here,
help me with this table.

1091
01:26:33,009 --> 01:26:34,601
Benjamin.

1092
01:26:34,711 --> 01:26:37,839
You're wasting your time, baby.
She's stone deaf.

1093
01:26:37,947 --> 01:26:41,974
Oh, and you'll be staying in
what was Mrs. DeSeroux's old room.

1094
01:26:42,085 --> 01:26:44,986
You're too big to be rooming
with anybody else.

1095
01:26:49,125 --> 01:26:51,719
<i>It's a funny thing about coming home.</i>

1096
01:26:52,395 --> 01:26:56,161
<i>Looks the same,
smells the same, feels the same.</i>

1097
01:26:58,935 --> 01:27:02,769
Did I ever tell you I've been struck
by lightning seven times?

1098
01:27:04,440 --> 01:27:07,807
Once when I was sitting in my truck,
just minding my own business.

1099
01:27:13,683 --> 01:27:17,119
<i>You realize what's changed is you.</i>

1100
01:27:19,789 --> 01:27:23,816
<i>And late one morning,
not long after I'd been back...</i>

1101
01:27:24,227 --> 01:27:25,558
Thank you.

1102
01:27:47,650 --> 01:27:48,708
Hey.

1103
01:27:53,289 --> 01:27:57,157
- Excuse me, is Queenie here?
- Daisy?

1104
01:28:00,930 --> 01:28:04,525
- It's me, Benjamin.
- Benjamin?

1105
01:28:08,271 --> 01:28:10,239
Oh, my God!

1106
01:28:11,541 --> 01:28:15,443
Of course it's you! Benjamin!

1107
01:28:17,547 --> 01:28:20,414
How are you?
It's been such a long time.

1108
01:28:20,516 --> 01:28:23,246
There's so much I want to know.
When did you get back?

1109
01:28:23,353 --> 01:28:24,752
Well, I got back a few weeks ago.

1110
01:28:24,854 --> 01:28:28,847
I spoke to Queenie, she said you were
in the war, somewhere at sea.

1111
01:28:28,958 --> 01:28:32,689
- We were so, so worried about you.
- Oh, I'm okay.

1112
01:28:32,795 --> 01:28:36,663
Well, look at you. You're so lovely.

1113
01:28:38,468 --> 01:28:40,231
You stopped writing.

1114
01:28:42,338 --> 01:28:47,435
"When I had left, she was a girl.
And a woman had taken her place.

1115
01:28:47,777 --> 01:28:50,940
"She was the most beautiful woman
I'd ever seen. "

1116
01:28:51,047 --> 01:28:52,378
Beautiful.

1117
01:28:54,584 --> 01:28:56,381
"The most beautiful. "

1118
01:28:58,187 --> 01:28:59,916
- You remember Grandma Fuller?
- Why, sure I do.

1119
01:29:00,023 --> 01:29:03,083
- She passed.
- I heard that. I'm sorry.

1120
01:29:03,192 --> 01:29:07,788
I just can't believe we're both here.
Must be fate.

1121
01:29:07,897 --> 01:29:09,865
No, no, what do they call it?

1122
01:29:09,966 --> 01:29:11,365
Kismet.

1123
01:29:11,467 --> 01:29:13,367
Do you know about Edgar Cayce,
the psychic?

1124
01:29:13,469 --> 01:29:14,458
I don't believe I...

1125
01:29:14,570 --> 01:29:17,437
He says
that everything is predetermined,

1126
01:29:17,540 --> 01:29:20,873
but I like to think of it as fate.

1127
01:29:24,080 --> 01:29:27,345
I'm not sure how it works,
but I'm glad it happened.

1128
01:29:27,450 --> 01:29:31,045
Have you been to Manhattan?
It's right across the river from me.

1129
01:29:31,154 --> 01:29:33,281
Now, I can see
the Empire State Building

1130
01:29:33,389 --> 01:29:35,152
if I stand on my bed.

1131
01:29:35,258 --> 01:29:37,249
What about you?
Where have you been?

1132
01:29:37,360 --> 01:29:40,955
Tell me everything. Last time you wrote,
you said you'd been to Russia.

1133
01:29:41,064 --> 01:29:45,228
I've always wanted to go to Russia.
Is it as cold as they say?

1134
01:29:45,335 --> 01:29:48,099
- Twice as cold.
- My goodness.

1135
01:29:48,705 --> 01:29:53,369
We always said you were different.
But I think you really are.

1136
01:29:55,478 --> 01:29:59,005
You wrote that you met somebody.
Did it work out?

1137
01:29:59,515 --> 01:30:01,176
It ran its course.

1138
01:30:02,552 --> 01:30:04,577
Hey, do you remember this?

1139
01:30:15,498 --> 01:30:18,194
"This is the picture
of Old Man Kangaroo

1140
01:30:18,301 --> 01:30:20,394
"at 5:00 in the afternoon. "

1141
01:30:22,238 --> 01:30:24,433
Would you like to have dinner?

1142
01:30:31,948 --> 01:30:34,849
<i>Did I tell you
that I danced for Balanchine?</i>

1143
01:30:35,551 --> 01:30:40,045
<i>Oh, he's a famous choreographer.
He said that I had perfect line.</i>

1144
01:30:41,791 --> 01:30:46,319
<i>You know, in a rehearsal once,
a dancer fell.</i>

1145
01:30:46,429 --> 01:30:49,227
<i>And he just...
He just put it right into the production.</i>

1146
01:30:49,332 --> 01:30:52,824
<i>I mean, can you imagine that?
Like in a... In a classical ballet?</i>

1147
01:30:52,935 --> 01:30:56,166
<i>You know, a dancer,
intentionally falling.</i>

1148
01:30:56,272 --> 01:30:59,901
<i>There's a whole new word
for dance now. It's called "abstract. "</i>

1149
01:31:00,009 --> 01:31:01,340
<i>No, he's not the only one, though.</i>

1150
01:31:01,444 --> 01:31:05,346
<i>There's Lincoln Kirstein
and Lucia Chase, and oh, my...</i>

1151
01:31:05,448 --> 01:31:07,939
<i>Oh, there's Agnes de Mille.</i>

1152
01:31:08,050 --> 01:31:10,109
<i>She's just torn up all those conventions,</i>

1153
01:31:10,219 --> 01:31:12,187
<i>you know,
all that straight-up-and-down stuff.</i>

1154
01:31:12,288 --> 01:31:15,485
<i>It's not about the formality of the dance,
it's about what the dancer's feeling.</i>

1155
01:31:15,591 --> 01:31:18,287
<i>As she told me
about this big new world,</i>

1156
01:31:18,394 --> 01:31:20,885
<i>names that didn't mean a thing to me,</i>

1157
01:31:20,997 --> 01:31:23,056
<i>I didn't really hear very much
of what she was saying.</i>

1158
01:31:23,166 --> 01:31:25,396
<i>It's new and it's modern
and it's American.</i>

1159
01:31:25,501 --> 01:31:28,664
They understand our vigor
and our physicality.

1160
01:31:28,771 --> 01:31:30,898
Oh, my God.
I've just been talking and talking.

1161
01:31:31,073 --> 01:31:35,510
No, no, I've enjoyed listening.
I didn't know you smoked.

1162
01:31:35,611 --> 01:31:37,135
I'm old enough.

1163
01:31:40,516 --> 01:31:43,007
I'm old enough for a lot of things.

1164
01:31:45,955 --> 01:31:48,389
In New York, we stay up all night,

1165
01:31:49,659 --> 01:31:52,457
watch the sun come up
over the warehouses.

1166
01:31:54,797 --> 01:31:57,095
There's always something to do.

1167
01:32:14,784 --> 01:32:16,877
I have to go back tomorrow.

1168
01:32:18,054 --> 01:32:20,181
- So soon.
- Wish I could stay.

1169
01:32:24,994 --> 01:32:28,157
Dancers don't need costumes
or scenery anymore.

1170
01:32:28,264 --> 01:32:31,791
I can imagine
dancing completely naked.

1171
01:32:33,102 --> 01:32:35,468
Have you read D.H. Lawrence?

1172
01:32:35,571 --> 01:32:37,664
- Well...
- His books were banned.

1173
01:32:37,773 --> 01:32:41,300
The words are like making love.

1174
01:33:25,855 --> 01:33:30,451
In our company,
we have to trust each other.

1175
01:33:35,765 --> 01:33:39,428
Sex is a part of it.

1176
01:33:43,839 --> 01:33:46,740
You know,
a lot of the dancers are lesbians.

1177
01:33:48,878 --> 01:33:51,972
There was one woman
who wanted to sleep with me.

1178
01:33:59,288 --> 01:34:02,280
- Does that upset you?
- Which part?

1179
01:34:03,392 --> 01:34:05,826
Somebody wanting to sleep with me.

1180
01:34:06,362 --> 01:34:07,522
You're a desirable woman.

1181
01:34:07,630 --> 01:34:11,361
I would think most of them
would want to sleep with you.

1182
01:34:11,467 --> 01:34:13,526
Let's go back to the house.

1183
01:34:14,503 --> 01:34:16,903
Or we could get a room somewhere.

1184
01:34:19,875 --> 01:34:23,072
- We could lay down your jacket.
- I don't know, Daisy.

1185
01:34:23,179 --> 01:34:28,515
It's not that I wouldn't like to or anything.
I think I'll just disappoint you.

1186
01:34:29,452 --> 01:34:32,512
Oh, Benjamin, I've been with older men.

1187
01:34:33,322 --> 01:34:35,313
You're going back to New York
in the morning.

1188
01:34:35,424 --> 01:34:37,756
You should be with your friends.

1189
01:34:38,761 --> 01:34:41,252
- You're only young once.
- Oh, I'm old enough.

1190
01:34:41,364 --> 01:34:43,958
Daisy, just not tonight, is all.

1191
01:34:57,513 --> 01:34:59,640
We could go hear some music.

1192
01:35:01,917 --> 01:35:04,613
<i>Our lives are defined by opportunities.</i>

1193
01:35:05,454 --> 01:35:07,445
<i>Even the ones we miss.</i>

1194
01:35:08,324 --> 01:35:11,953
You look so handsome
and so distinguished.

1195
01:35:12,061 --> 01:35:14,222
They're saying the hurricane's
gonna miss us, blow right on by.

1196
01:35:14,330 --> 01:35:18,926
- Oh, that's great.
- I'll stay under the blankets with Mother.

1197
01:35:19,035 --> 01:35:23,096
She says nothing... Benjamin?

1198
01:35:25,041 --> 01:35:26,099
"Things were becoming different... "

1199
01:35:26,208 --> 01:35:27,368
<i>...for me.</i>

1200
01:35:27,476 --> 01:35:31,071
<i>My hair had very little gray
and grew like weeds.</i>

1201
01:35:31,180 --> 01:35:34,946
<i>My sense of smell was keener.
My hearing, more acute.</i>

1202
01:35:35,051 --> 01:35:37,679
<i>I could walk further and faster.</i>

1203
01:35:37,787 --> 01:35:43,555
<i>While everybody else was aging,
I was getting younger, all alone.</i>

1204
01:35:46,595 --> 01:35:47,823
Come in.

1205
01:35:49,231 --> 01:35:50,528
Benjamin.

1206
01:35:51,534 --> 01:35:54,731
- Do you remember me?
- Well, sure I do, Mr. Button.

1207
01:35:55,438 --> 01:35:58,999
- What happened to you?
- Darn foot. Got infected, so...

1208
01:36:00,676 --> 01:36:01,904
Welcome home, my friend.

1209
01:36:04,613 --> 01:36:07,707
I see you're still drinking
your Sazerac with whiskey.

1210
01:36:07,817 --> 01:36:09,045
Creature of habit.

1211
01:36:09,151 --> 01:36:11,244
You still visiting the house
on Bourbon Street?

1212
01:36:11,353 --> 01:36:13,082
Not for a long time.

1213
01:36:14,690 --> 01:36:16,783
Interesting times, though.

1214
01:36:16,892 --> 01:36:21,329
We went from making 40,000
to nearly half a million buttons a day.

1215
01:36:21,430 --> 01:36:23,421
We employed 10 times
the number of people.

1216
01:36:23,532 --> 01:36:26,023
We were operating around the clock.

1217
01:36:30,606 --> 01:36:31,971
Damn shame.

1218
01:36:33,109 --> 01:36:36,044
The war has been kind
to the button industry.

1219
01:36:38,781 --> 01:36:40,112
You know,

1220
01:36:42,384 --> 01:36:45,717
I'm sick.
I don't know how much longer I have.

1221
01:36:45,821 --> 01:36:48,654
- I'm sorry to hear that, Mr. Button.
- No...

1222
01:36:50,059 --> 01:36:53,119
I don't have any people.
I keep to myself.

1223
01:36:55,631 --> 01:36:58,623
I hope you don't mind,
but, whenever possible,

1224
01:36:58,734 --> 01:37:00,725
I'd enjoy your company.

1225
01:37:00,836 --> 01:37:03,327
I'll certainly do what I can.

1226
01:37:06,642 --> 01:37:09,543
Benjamin, do you know anything
about buttons?

1227
01:37:13,149 --> 01:37:17,779
Now, Button's Buttons has been
in our family for 124 years.

1228
01:37:18,454 --> 01:37:23,050
My grandfather was a tailor,
and he had a small shop in Richmond.

1229
01:37:23,159 --> 01:37:25,559
After the Civil War,
he moved to New Orleans,

1230
01:37:25,661 --> 01:37:30,689
where my father had the wisdom
to make our own buttons.

1231
01:37:30,800 --> 01:37:35,669
So, with his help,
the tailor shop grew to this.

1232
01:37:36,405 --> 01:37:38,999
And today, I can't sew a stitch.

1233
01:37:43,212 --> 01:37:45,544
That's very, very interesting.

1234
01:37:49,018 --> 01:37:51,612
You sure have done well for yourself.

1235
01:37:52,555 --> 01:37:56,616
So, what can I do for you, Mr. Button?

1236
01:37:59,161 --> 01:38:02,153
Benjamin? You're my son.

1237
01:38:09,705 --> 01:38:12,333
I'm so sorry I never told you before.

1238
01:38:14,510 --> 01:38:17,877
You were born
the night the Great War ended.

1239
01:38:19,782 --> 01:38:23,479
Your mother died giving birth to you.

1240
01:38:24,987 --> 01:38:27,182
I thought you were a monster.

1241
01:38:30,759 --> 01:38:34,024
I promised your mother
I'd make sure you were safe.

1242
01:38:40,469 --> 01:38:42,903
I should never have abandoned you.

1243
01:38:47,042 --> 01:38:48,373
My mother?

1244
01:38:49,745 --> 01:38:52,680
At the summer house
on Lake Pontchartrain.

1245
01:38:52,781 --> 01:38:56,217
When I was a boy,
I'd love to wake up before anyone else,

1246
01:38:56,318 --> 01:38:59,310
run down to that lake
and watch the day begin.

1247
01:39:00,990 --> 01:39:03,618
It was as if I was the only one alive.

1248
01:39:05,461 --> 01:39:08,157
I fell in love the first time I saw her.

1249
01:39:08,731 --> 01:39:11,359
Your mother's name
was Caroline Murphy.

1250
01:39:12,001 --> 01:39:14,868
She worked
in your grandfather's kitchen.

1251
01:39:18,140 --> 01:39:19,801
She's from Dublin.

1252
01:39:20,476 --> 01:39:24,879
In 1903, Caroline and all her brothers
and sisters came to live here,

1253
01:39:24,980 --> 01:39:26,504
in New Orleans.

1254
01:39:28,651 --> 01:39:31,484
I'd find excuses
to go down to that kitchen

1255
01:39:32,321 --> 01:39:34,448
just so I could look at her.

1256
01:39:40,829 --> 01:39:44,560
April 25th, 1918.
Happiest day of my life.

1257
01:39:45,334 --> 01:39:47,564
The day I married your mother.

1258
01:39:49,305 --> 01:39:51,432
Why didn't you just tell me?

1259
01:39:52,308 --> 01:39:55,141
I plan on leaving everything I have
to you.

1260
01:39:56,679 --> 01:39:59,113
- I have to go.
- Where?

1261
01:40:00,182 --> 01:40:01,547
Home.

1262
01:40:02,251 --> 01:40:03,582
And what does he think, anyway?

1263
01:40:03,686 --> 01:40:04,983
He thinks he can just show up

1264
01:40:05,087 --> 01:40:06,952
and everything's
supposed to be fine and dandy.

1265
01:40:07,056 --> 01:40:09,650
Everybody's just supposed to be friends.

1266
01:40:09,758 --> 01:40:12,659
Well, he got another thing coming,
that's for sure.

1267
01:40:12,761 --> 01:40:16,162
God be my witness,
he got another thing coming.

1268
01:40:16,265 --> 01:40:19,325
He left us $18 that night you was found.

1269
01:40:19,435 --> 01:40:21,266
Eighteen ratty dollars

1270
01:40:21,370 --> 01:40:23,065
- and a filthy diaper.
- Good night, Mama.

1271
01:40:24,440 --> 01:40:25,634
Good night, baby.

1272
01:40:38,921 --> 01:40:43,255
Did I ever tell you
I was struck by lightning seven times?

1273
01:40:45,060 --> 01:40:47,085
Once, I was walking my dog
down the road.

1274
01:40:52,101 --> 01:40:55,935
I'm blind in the one eye,
can't hardly hear,

1275
01:40:57,206 --> 01:41:01,802
get twitches and shakes out of nowhere,
always losing my line of thought.

1276
01:41:03,379 --> 01:41:05,040
But you know what?

1277
01:41:05,814 --> 01:41:08,749
God keeps reminding me
I'm lucky to be alive.

1278
01:41:14,523 --> 01:41:16,047
Storm's coming.

1279
01:41:43,986 --> 01:41:46,216
May I help you, sir?
Up the stairs, first bedroom.

1280
01:41:46,321 --> 01:41:47,379
Thank you.

1281
01:42:03,272 --> 01:42:04,500
Wake up.

1282
01:42:07,042 --> 01:42:08,907
Let's get you dressed.

1283
01:42:36,338 --> 01:42:37,965
Now that's something.

1284
01:42:41,276 --> 01:42:42,607
Thank you.

1285
01:43:42,771 --> 01:43:46,730
<i>You can be mad as a mad dog
at the way things went.</i>

1286
01:43:46,842 --> 01:43:49,242
<i>You can swear and curse the Fates.</i>

1287
01:43:50,846 --> 01:43:53,041
<i>But when it comes to the end,</i>

1288
01:43:54,283 --> 01:43:56,012
<i>you have to let go.</i>

1289
01:44:18,006 --> 01:44:20,600
Well, it sure is a beautiful service.

1290
01:44:22,477 --> 01:44:25,275
He'll be buried
right next to your mother.

1291
01:44:26,748 --> 01:44:28,375
You're my mother.

1292
01:44:32,221 --> 01:44:33,449
My baby.

1293
01:44:38,060 --> 01:44:40,187
<i>Now, I'd never seen New York.</i>

1294
01:46:08,383 --> 01:46:11,750
- Excuse me, I'm a friend of Daisy's.
- Right this way.

1295
01:46:12,821 --> 01:46:18,157
- Daisy has company. Daisy! Daisy!
- Yes!

1296
01:46:18,560 --> 01:46:21,825
- We need the wardrobe.
- Is somebody looking for me?

1297
01:46:24,433 --> 01:46:25,463
- Benjamin.
- Hi.

1298
01:46:25,563 --> 01:46:26,623
- Benjamin.
- Hi.

1299
01:46:27,936 --> 01:46:31,702
- What are you doing here?
- Thought I'd come visit.

1300
01:46:31,807 --> 01:46:35,265
Spend some time with you, if I could.

1301
01:46:35,377 --> 01:46:41,247
Oh, well, I wish you would've called.
You took me by surprise.

1302
01:46:42,617 --> 01:46:46,747
- You can just throw them out.
- No. Thank you, they're lovely.

1303
01:46:47,389 --> 01:46:52,190
I couldn't take my eyes off of you.
I thought you were mesmerizing.

1304
01:46:54,229 --> 01:46:57,027
Thank you.
That's very kind of you to say.

1305
01:47:02,371 --> 01:47:04,396
I better get changed.
A group of us are going to a party.

1306
01:47:04,506 --> 01:47:07,771
- Would you want to come?
- Someone told me about a restaurant

1307
01:47:07,876 --> 01:47:09,138
I thought you might enjoy.

1308
01:47:09,244 --> 01:47:11,735
I made a reservation, just in case.

1309
01:47:11,847 --> 01:47:14,839
Just, all the dancers go out
after the show. You're...

1310
01:47:14,950 --> 01:47:18,750
You're welcome to come with us.
I'll get changed. All right?

1311
01:47:25,227 --> 01:47:27,320
She choreographs
for the Ballets Russes.

1312
01:47:27,429 --> 01:47:28,726
She's divine.

1313
01:47:29,364 --> 01:47:31,195
You were breathtaking.

1314
01:47:36,905 --> 01:47:38,133
Sweetie.

1315
01:47:39,307 --> 01:47:42,174
This is David.
He dances with the company.

1316
01:47:43,178 --> 01:47:45,203
- This is Benjamin.
- Who?

1317
01:47:45,313 --> 01:47:48,544
- I told you about him.
- Oh, yeah. How you doing?

1318
01:47:48,650 --> 01:47:52,108
- I'll go get you a drink.
- All right. Thanks.

1319
01:47:59,828 --> 01:48:02,991
So, you were a friend
of her grandmother's?

1320
01:48:03,098 --> 01:48:04,998
Or something like that?

1321
01:48:06,168 --> 01:48:07,931
Something like that.

1322
01:48:08,270 --> 01:48:09,794
Hey, excuse me.

1323
01:48:32,160 --> 01:48:33,388
Come on.

1324
01:48:54,749 --> 01:48:55,807
Hey!

1325
01:48:56,785 --> 01:48:59,276
Now, I had no idea you were coming.

1326
01:49:00,322 --> 01:49:01,846
Lord, Benjamin.

1327
01:49:04,459 --> 01:49:08,327
What did you expect?
What, you want me to drop everything?

1328
01:49:08,430 --> 01:49:10,398
Now, this is my life.

1329
01:49:10,499 --> 01:49:12,933
Babe! You going downtown?

1330
01:49:17,906 --> 01:49:21,000
Come on. You'll have a good time.

1331
01:49:21,877 --> 01:49:23,367
There's lots of musicians,
interesting people.

1332
01:49:23,478 --> 01:49:26,379
You don't have to do that.
This is my fault.

1333
01:49:27,482 --> 01:49:28,915
I should've called.

1334
01:49:29,017 --> 01:49:31,815
I thought I'd come here

1335
01:49:31,920 --> 01:49:34,650
and sweep you off your feet
or something.

1336
01:49:36,157 --> 01:49:40,617
- Daisy! Come on! Let's go.
- Be right there.

1337
01:49:42,430 --> 01:49:43,795
Seems nice.

1338
01:49:45,166 --> 01:49:46,758
Do you love him?

1339
01:49:49,905 --> 01:49:51,270
I think so.

1340
01:49:53,408 --> 01:49:55,069
I'm happy for you.

1341
01:49:57,012 --> 01:49:59,105
Maybe I'll see you at home.

1342
01:50:01,750 --> 01:50:02,842
Okay.

1343
01:50:04,886 --> 01:50:06,615
I enjoyed the show!

1344
01:50:14,262 --> 01:50:18,756
He came to tell me his father had died.

1345
01:50:20,268 --> 01:50:26,434
- You couldn't have known.
- I was 23. I... I just didn't care.

1346
01:50:29,010 --> 01:50:30,375
What did you do next?

1347
01:50:30,478 --> 01:50:37,407
Some photographs, I think,
in the front of my bag.

1348
01:50:39,521 --> 01:50:43,617
I was as good a dancer
as I was ever gonna be.

1349
01:50:45,527 --> 01:50:47,461
For five years, I...

1350
01:50:50,231 --> 01:50:51,994
I danced everywhere.

1351
01:50:53,468 --> 01:50:56,960
London, Vienna, Prague.

1352
01:50:57,572 --> 01:50:59,437
I've never seen these.

1353
01:51:02,777 --> 01:51:03,835
Mom.

1354
01:51:05,146 --> 01:51:07,842
You never talked about your dancing.

1355
01:51:07,949 --> 01:51:09,940
Well, I was the only American

1356
01:51:10,051 --> 01:51:14,988
to be invited to dance
with the Bolshoi, sugar.

1357
01:51:16,858 --> 01:51:18,849
<i>It was glorious.</i>

1358
01:51:23,331 --> 01:51:27,028
<i>But Benjamin was never far
from my thoughts.</i>

1359
01:51:30,205 --> 01:51:33,766
<i>And I'd find myself saying...</i>

1360
01:51:33,875 --> 01:51:35,672
Good night, Benjamin.

1361
01:51:37,679 --> 01:51:41,308
- "Good night, Daisy. "
- He said that?

1362
01:51:43,485 --> 01:51:44,645
"Life wasn't all that complicated.

1363
01:51:45,520 --> 01:51:48,284
<i>"If you want, you might say
I was looking for something. "</i>

1364
01:51:57,766 --> 01:52:00,735
Benjamin?
Mrs. La Tourneau just passed.

1365
01:52:07,142 --> 01:52:10,805
- Letter for Mr. Benjamin Button?
- That'd be me.

1366
01:52:13,715 --> 01:52:15,046
Thank you.

1367
01:52:41,376 --> 01:52:43,276
Miss Daisy Fuller.

1368
01:52:43,378 --> 01:52:46,176
- Just a minute. Please have a seat.
- Sure.

1369
01:52:53,655 --> 01:52:58,058
<i>Sometimes we're on a collision course
and we just don't know it.</i>

1370
01:52:58,626 --> 01:53:03,120
<i>Whether it's by accident or by design,
there's not a thing we can do about it.</i>

1371
01:53:05,967 --> 01:53:09,027
<i>A woman in Paris was on her way
to go shopping.</i>

1372
01:53:10,371 --> 01:53:14,137
<i>But she had forgotten her coat,
went back to get it.</i>

1373
01:53:14,242 --> 01:53:16,403
<i>When she had gotten her coat,
the phone had rung.</i>

1374
01:53:16,511 --> 01:53:19,503
<i>So she had stopped to answer it
and talked for a couple of minutes.</i>

1375
01:53:21,015 --> 01:53:22,812
<i>While the woman was on the phone,</i>

1376
01:53:22,917 --> 01:53:27,081
<i>Daisy was rehearsing for a performance
at the Paris Opera House.</i>

1377
01:53:27,188 --> 01:53:29,952
<i>And while she was rehearsing,
the woman, off the phone now,</i>

1378
01:53:30,058 --> 01:53:32,356
<i>had gone outside to get a taxi.</i>

1379
01:53:36,898 --> 01:53:39,196
<i>Now, a taxi driver had
dropped off a fare earlier,</i>

1380
01:53:39,300 --> 01:53:41,996
<i>and had stopped to get a cup of coffee.</i>

1381
01:53:42,904 --> 01:53:45,634
<i>And all the while, Daisy was rehearsing.</i>

1382
01:53:49,177 --> 01:53:51,675
<i>And this cab driver,
who dropped off the earlier fare</i>

1383
01:53:51,780 --> 01:53:53,748
<i>and had stopped
to get the cup of coffee,</i>

1384
01:53:53,848 --> 01:53:55,543
<i>he picked up the lady
who was going shopping</i>

1385
01:53:55,650 --> 01:53:58,346
<i>and had missed getting the earlier cab.</i>

1386
01:53:59,320 --> 01:54:01,720
<i>The taxi had to stop
for a man crossing the street,</i>

1387
01:54:01,823 --> 01:54:04,621
<i>who had left for work five minutes later
than he normally did</i>

1388
01:54:04,726 --> 01:54:07,217
<i>because he forgot to set his alarm.</i>

1389
01:54:08,029 --> 01:54:11,294
<i>While that man, late for work,
was crossing the street,</i>

1390
01:54:11,399 --> 01:54:14,835
<i>Daisy had finished rehearsing
and was taking a shower.</i>

1391
01:54:15,370 --> 01:54:16,667
<i>And while Daisy was showering,</i>

1392
01:54:16,771 --> 01:54:20,400
<i>the taxi was waiting outside a boutique
for the woman to pick up a package</i>

1393
01:54:20,508 --> 01:54:21,600
<i>which hadn't been wrapped yet,</i>

1394
01:54:21,709 --> 01:54:23,506
<i>because the girl
who was supposed to wrap it</i>

1395
01:54:23,611 --> 01:54:27,206
<i>had broken up with her boyfriend
the night before and forgot.</i>

1396
01:54:27,882 --> 01:54:31,079
<i>When the package was wrapped,
the woman, who was back in the cab,</i>

1397
01:54:31,186 --> 01:54:32,813
<i>was blocked by a delivery truck.</i>

1398
01:54:32,921 --> 01:54:35,651
<i>All the while,
Daisy was getting dressed.</i>

1399
01:54:37,158 --> 01:54:40,525
<i>The delivery truck pulled away,
and the taxi was able to move</i>

1400
01:54:40,628 --> 01:54:42,721
<i>while Daisy, the last to be dressed,</i>

1401
01:54:42,831 --> 01:54:46,358
<i>waited for one of her friends
who had broken a shoelace.</i>

1402
01:54:46,801 --> 01:54:49,736
<i>While the taxi was stopped,
waiting for a traffic light,</i>

1403
01:54:49,838 --> 01:54:53,740
<i>Daisy and her friend
came out the back of the theater.</i>

1404
01:54:53,842 --> 01:54:57,209
<i>And if only one thing
had happened differently,</i>

1405
01:54:57,312 --> 01:54:59,405
<i>if that shoelace hadn't broken</i>

1406
01:54:59,514 --> 01:55:02,005
<i>or that delivery truck
had moved moments earlier</i>

1407
01:55:02,116 --> 01:55:03,981
<i>or that package
had been wrapped and ready</i>

1408
01:55:04,085 --> 01:55:06,815
<i>because the girl hadn't broken up
with her boyfriend,</i>

1409
01:55:06,921 --> 01:55:10,584
<i>or that man had set his alarm
and got up five minutes earlier</i>

1410
01:55:10,692 --> 01:55:13,855
<i>or that taxi driver hadn't stopped
for a cup of coffee</i>

1411
01:55:13,962 --> 01:55:17,955
<i>or that woman had remembered
her coat and got into an earlier cab,</i>

1412
01:55:18,533 --> 01:55:21,195
<i>Daisy and her friend
would have crossed the street</i>

1413
01:55:21,302 --> 01:55:23,736
<i>and the taxi would have driven by.</i>

1414
01:55:34,816 --> 01:55:36,545
<i>But, life being what it is,</i>

1415
01:55:36,651 --> 01:55:39,643
<i>a series of intersecting lives
and incidents</i>

1416
01:55:39,754 --> 01:55:41,517
<i>out of anyone's control,</i>

1417
01:55:42,390 --> 01:55:45,086
<i>that taxi did not go by,</i>

1418
01:55:45,193 --> 01:55:48,026
<i>and that driver was
momentarily distracted.</i>

1419
01:55:49,030 --> 01:55:49,997
<i>Daisy!</i>

1420
01:55:50,231 --> 01:55:51,459
<i>And that taxi hit Daisy.</i>

1421
01:55:51,566 --> 01:55:53,261
Daisy! Help!

1422
01:55:56,437 --> 01:55:58,405
<i>And her leg was crushed.</i>

1423
01:56:05,813 --> 01:56:06,973
Daisy?

1424
01:56:11,286 --> 01:56:13,811
- Who told you?
- Your friend wired me.

1425
01:56:14,889 --> 01:56:18,950
Very kind of you to come all this way
to see that I was all right.

1426
01:56:20,528 --> 01:56:22,519
You'd do the same for me.

1427
01:56:24,465 --> 01:56:25,659
My God.

1428
01:56:27,802 --> 01:56:31,260
Look at you. You're perfect.

1429
01:56:34,108 --> 01:56:38,602
I wish you hadn't come here.
I don't want you to see me like this.

1430
01:56:45,053 --> 01:56:47,351
<i>Her leg had been broken in five places.</i>

1431
01:56:47,455 --> 01:56:50,549
<i>And with therapy and time,
she might walk again.</i>

1432
01:56:52,126 --> 01:56:53,991
<i>But she'd never dance.</i>

1433
01:56:55,630 --> 01:56:58,064
I'm gonna take you home with me.

1434
01:56:58,166 --> 01:57:00,930
- I want to look after you.
- I'm not going back to New Orleans.

1435
01:57:01,035 --> 01:57:03,196
Then I'll stay here in Paris.

1436
01:57:03,838 --> 01:57:06,773
Don't you understand?
I don't want your help.

1437
01:57:07,875 --> 01:57:12,209
I know I'm feeling sorry for myself,
but I don't want to be with you.

1438
01:57:12,313 --> 01:57:16,044
Tried to tell you that in New York.
You don't listen.

1439
01:57:17,585 --> 01:57:19,553
You might change your mind.

1440
01:57:19,654 --> 01:57:22,589
We are not little children
anymore, Benjamin.

1441
01:57:24,625 --> 01:57:27,856
Just stay out of my life.

1442
01:57:50,718 --> 01:57:53,949
<i>I was awfully cruel.</i>

1443
01:57:55,056 --> 01:58:00,460
He didn't understand.
I couldn't have him see me like that.

1444
01:58:03,164 --> 01:58:04,529
"I didn't leave right away.

1445
01:58:07,168 --> 01:58:10,467
<i>"I stayed in Paris for a while
to look out for her. "</i>

1446
01:58:14,075 --> 01:58:15,906
I never knew that.

